1
00:00:00,042 --> 00:00:02,127
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

2
00:00:02,211 --> 00:00:04,046
This place is so pretty.

3
00:00:05,172 --> 00:00:06,507
I wonder if they have butter rice cakes.

4
00:00:06,590 --> 00:00:10,302
FIFTH BOOK: <i>THE HAPPY PRINCE</i>

5
00:00:10,385 --> 00:00:11,803
It's so cute.

6
00:00:12,596 --> 00:00:13,722
What is this place?

7
00:00:16,016 --> 00:00:18,352
Let's see. Hocrates!

8
00:00:22,022 --> 00:00:22,940
Hello.

9
00:00:23,732 --> 00:00:25,400
- Hello.
- Hello.

10
00:00:25,526 --> 00:00:26,443
It's you, right?

11
00:00:26,818 --> 00:00:28,570
- The sibling musicians.
- Yes.

12
00:00:28,695 --> 00:00:30,322
- Come here and take a seat.
- Thank you.

13
00:00:30,405 --> 00:00:31,490
It's you, right?

14
00:00:31,573 --> 00:00:33,158
- AKMU!
- That's right.

15
00:00:33,242 --> 00:00:34,785
- Right?
- How did you know?

16
00:00:35,327 --> 00:00:37,120
You can take a seat here.

17
00:00:38,539 --> 00:00:39,581
- Yes.
- AKMU.

18
00:00:39,665 --> 00:00:40,582
- Yes.
- All right.

19
00:00:40,666 --> 00:00:43,252
Located in the cutest neighborhood
in the world,

20
00:00:43,335 --> 00:00:44,586
Kangho-dong...

21
00:00:45,295 --> 00:00:47,422
- Yes.
- That's why this place is so cute.

22
00:00:47,506 --> 00:00:50,050
This is Hodong's Bookshop.

23
00:00:50,133 --> 00:00:51,843
A big welcome!

24
00:00:53,595 --> 00:00:55,055
So cute!

25
00:00:57,182 --> 00:00:58,517
By the way,

26
00:00:59,017 --> 00:01:00,978
you two look
even more radiant and cool now.

27
00:01:01,061 --> 00:01:02,563
- Do you think so?
- Really?

28
00:01:03,772 --> 00:01:04,856
Wait a minute.

29
00:01:06,608 --> 00:01:08,902
Have we met before?

30
00:01:09,361 --> 00:01:11,113
I thought we were meeting

31
00:01:11,488 --> 00:01:12,948
the 2,000-year-old Hocrates.

32
00:01:13,031 --> 00:01:14,616
I did think we'd met before.

33
00:01:14,700 --> 00:01:15,534
I see.

34
00:01:15,617 --> 00:01:17,869
Do you remember where?

35
00:01:17,953 --> 00:01:20,622
We were on a show five years ago.

36
00:01:20,706 --> 00:01:23,959
- That's right.
- You look a lot like Kang Ho-dong.

37
00:01:24,042 --> 00:01:26,253
- You look so alike.
- As soon as I got here, I told the staff

38
00:01:26,336 --> 00:01:27,796
that I wanted to say hi to Mr. Kang,

39
00:01:27,879 --> 00:01:30,215
- but they said you weren't him.
- That's right.

40
00:01:30,299 --> 00:01:32,968
When I met Mr. Kang Ho-dong--

41
00:01:33,051 --> 00:01:34,553
- What's he like?
- He was adorable.

42
00:01:34,636 --> 00:01:36,221
- I see.
- He was super cute

43
00:01:36,597 --> 00:01:38,515
and he was also very sweet.

44
00:01:38,599 --> 00:01:42,811
HYPERFOCUSED ON COMPLIMENTS NOT FOR HIM
He had a sweet smile like a baby's.

45
00:01:42,978 --> 00:01:46,356
And so do you. You're also...

46
00:01:46,773 --> 00:01:49,234
Like that?

47
00:01:49,318 --> 00:01:52,529
IT'S LIKE HE WAS POSSESSED
I don't think that was me.

48
00:01:52,946 --> 00:01:54,656
The similarity is uncanny.

49
00:01:58,076 --> 00:01:59,828
- He did that, too.
- It's strange.

50
00:01:59,911 --> 00:02:02,205
- How curious.
- It's like I'm him, but I'm not.

51
00:02:02,998 --> 00:02:04,249
I'm someone made-up.

52
00:02:04,916 --> 00:02:07,502
NOTICE: HE'S CUTER THAN THE MAN
THEY MET 5 YEARS AGO ON MEN ON A MISSION

53
00:02:07,586 --> 00:02:09,713
- Let's say we only met today.
- Right.

54
00:02:10,005 --> 00:02:12,132
- Let's just keep it casual.
- Okay.

55
00:02:12,215 --> 00:02:13,759
Follow our hearts.

56
00:02:13,842 --> 00:02:15,052
- Okay.
- Sounds great.

57
00:02:15,552 --> 00:02:17,137
Okay. Let's go over this now.

58
00:02:17,220 --> 00:02:18,847
What are your names?

59
00:02:19,139 --> 00:02:20,766
- We're called AKMU.
- Yes.

60
00:02:20,974 --> 00:02:22,392
My name is Lee Chan-hyuk.

61
00:02:22,476 --> 00:02:23,894
My name is Lee Su-hyun.

62
00:02:23,977 --> 00:02:25,896
Okay, but from what I know,

63
00:02:26,146 --> 00:02:27,939
the name wasn't originally AKMU.

64
00:02:28,023 --> 00:02:29,608
- It was Akdong Musician.
- Yes.

65
00:02:29,691 --> 00:02:31,485
Su-hyun came up with that name.

66
00:02:31,568 --> 00:02:33,445
That's right. You know a lot.

67
00:02:33,528 --> 00:02:35,489
- I do.
- We were singing one day,

68
00:02:35,572 --> 00:02:38,158
going, "We are Akdong Musician."

69
00:02:38,241 --> 00:02:40,577
"We are musicians,

70
00:02:40,661 --> 00:02:42,496
- Akdong Musician." Like that.
- Right.

71
00:02:42,663 --> 00:02:44,581
- We were just having fun.
- I see.

72
00:02:44,665 --> 00:02:46,291
And I went and told our dad,

73
00:02:46,375 --> 00:02:50,462
"We named our band Akdong Musician."

74
00:02:50,671 --> 00:02:54,049
Then our dad added
more meaning to the name.

75
00:02:54,257 --> 00:02:56,802
<i>"Ak" </i>as in "joyful,"
and <i>"dong"</i> as in "child."

76
00:02:56,885 --> 00:02:59,388
So, "joyful child musicians."

77
00:02:59,554 --> 00:03:00,889
That's Akdong Musician.

78
00:03:00,972 --> 00:03:02,724
- Not <i>"akdong"</i> as in "rascal."
- No.

79
00:03:02,808 --> 00:03:04,810
- It's "joyful children."
- Yes.

80
00:03:04,893 --> 00:03:06,228
But then,

81
00:03:06,311 --> 00:03:08,188
why did you change your name to AKMU?

82
00:03:08,271 --> 00:03:09,356
WHY THE NAME CHANGE?

83
00:03:09,898 --> 00:03:11,274
After my military service,

84
00:03:11,942 --> 00:03:14,986
- I thought the <i>"dong"</i> as in "child"
- Yes?

85
00:03:15,153 --> 00:03:17,989
wouldn't be good for us
as musicians in the long run.

86
00:03:18,490 --> 00:03:19,908
We're going to get old,

87
00:03:19,991 --> 00:03:21,785
and our music will be more mature.

88
00:03:22,536 --> 00:03:24,996
I thought the old name wouldn't suit that.

89
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:28,041
FROM THE CUTE "AKDONG MUSICIAN"
That's why we changed it.

90
00:03:28,125 --> 00:03:29,584
TO THE MORE MATURE "AKMU"

91
00:03:29,918 --> 00:03:31,545
And what are your occupations?

92
00:03:32,129 --> 00:03:34,631
We actually have a lot of jobs.

93
00:03:34,965 --> 00:03:37,884
We recently started a company.

94
00:03:37,968 --> 00:03:40,804
INDEPENDENT LABEL
<i>It's called Cemter of Inspiration.</i>

95
00:03:40,887 --> 00:03:44,933
<i>We create music and art,</i>
<i>put on exhibitions,</i>

96
00:03:45,016 --> 00:03:47,853
<i>and basically do whatever we want.</i>

97
00:03:48,603 --> 00:03:52,774
I call myself the "Head of the Cemter."

98
00:03:52,858 --> 00:03:55,193
- Okay.
- And I'm the princess.

99
00:03:59,573 --> 00:04:00,657
PRIN...
Yes.

100
00:04:00,741 --> 00:04:02,159
Here's the thing.

101
00:04:02,534 --> 00:04:05,162
THE HEAD OF CEMTER PROVIDES EXPLANATION
This is what's interesting.

102
00:04:05,245 --> 00:04:07,080
People in our company

103
00:04:07,372 --> 00:04:08,874
actually call her "Princess."

104
00:04:09,666 --> 00:04:11,251
You didn't force them.

105
00:04:11,334 --> 00:04:12,711
- Not at all.
- Voluntarily?

106
00:04:12,794 --> 00:04:13,712
- Yes.
- I see.

107
00:04:13,795 --> 00:04:15,756
I told her to choose her own title.

108
00:04:15,839 --> 00:04:17,674
She chose "Princess." I said "sure."

109
00:04:17,758 --> 00:04:19,259
And people call her that.

110
00:04:19,342 --> 00:04:20,844
What's your role, Princess?

111
00:04:21,344 --> 00:04:23,638
Existing as a princess.

112
00:04:24,181 --> 00:04:25,056
LOL

113
00:04:26,308 --> 00:04:27,642
You're quite unusual as well.

114
00:04:28,435 --> 00:04:29,644
AN UNUSUAL GROUP OF A 2,000-YEAR-OLD
PHILOSOPHER, PRINCESS, AND HEAD OF CEMTER

115
00:04:29,728 --> 00:04:30,604
Quite unusual.

116
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:33,482
What book are you here to sell?

117
00:04:34,232 --> 00:04:36,109
- It's a book I love.
- Okay.

118
00:04:36,193 --> 00:04:37,736
I didn't want to sell it.

119
00:04:37,819 --> 00:04:39,613
But I've read it many times,

120
00:04:39,696 --> 00:04:42,699
- and I wanted more people to read it.
- I see.

121
00:04:43,283 --> 00:04:46,161
We're here to sell <i>The Happy Prince</i>.

122
00:04:46,244 --> 00:04:48,413
- Oh, this book.
- Yes.

123
00:04:48,497 --> 00:04:50,832
From what I hear,

124
00:04:50,916 --> 00:04:52,459
this book is out of print.

125
00:04:52,542 --> 00:04:54,044
- That's right.
- So instead,

126
00:04:54,628 --> 00:04:56,171
how about this one?

127
00:04:56,254 --> 00:04:58,298
<i>Nine Stories by Oscar Wilde</i>.

128
00:04:58,465 --> 00:05:01,134
This book has the same stories,

129
00:05:01,218 --> 00:05:02,719
- Okay.
- but different translations.

130
00:05:02,803 --> 00:05:04,638
I love this book,

131
00:05:04,888 --> 00:05:07,224
so I've read different versions, but...

132
00:05:07,307 --> 00:05:08,934
- You know this version?
- I do.

133
00:05:09,601 --> 00:05:12,813
You can read this version first.

134
00:05:12,896 --> 00:05:14,105
- Okay.
- When you can,

135
00:05:14,189 --> 00:05:16,358
I recommend you read this version, too.

136
00:05:16,441 --> 00:05:17,776
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

137
00:05:18,443 --> 00:05:19,653
AKMU'S FAVORITE BOOK

138
00:05:19,736 --> 00:05:21,071
<i>NINE STORIES BY OSCAR WILDE</i>

139
00:05:21,154 --> 00:05:23,490
A FULL TRANSLATION
OF NINE SHORT STORIES BY OSCAR WILDE

140
00:05:23,573 --> 00:05:24,866
INCLUDING <i>THE HAPPY PRINCE</i>

141
00:05:24,950 --> 00:05:27,160
<i>THE HAPPY PRINCE AND OTHER STORIES</i>
SIX SHORT STORIES BY OSCAR WILDE

142
00:05:27,244 --> 00:05:29,246
THE ORIGINAL TEXT AND KOREAN TRANSLATION
ARE PRINTED SIDE BY SIDE

143
00:05:29,329 --> 00:05:30,455
CURRENTLY OUT OF PRINT

144
00:05:30,539 --> 00:05:33,416
When I fly,

145
00:05:33,500 --> 00:05:36,169
I always bring this book with me
on the plane.

146
00:05:37,504 --> 00:05:38,922
In this book,

147
00:05:39,923 --> 00:05:42,676
there are six different stories.

148
00:05:43,260 --> 00:05:46,346
My favorite one is <i>The Happy Prince</i>.

149
00:05:47,180 --> 00:05:48,306
It's my favorite chapter.

150
00:05:48,932 --> 00:05:51,226
<i>There's this beautiful statue.</i>

151
00:05:51,309 --> 00:05:52,561
THE HAPPY PRINCE STATUE BECAME UNHAPPY
AFTER SEEING THE POOR PEOPLE

152
00:05:52,644 --> 00:05:56,523
<i>One day, he tells a swallow</i>
<i>to take all of his rubies</i>

153
00:05:56,606 --> 00:05:59,860
<i>and give them to poor children.</i>

154
00:06:00,527 --> 00:06:03,655
<i>The swallow happily does as he wishes,</i>

155
00:06:03,738 --> 00:06:06,199
<i>and dies together with him in the cold.</i>

156
00:06:06,283 --> 00:06:07,242
<i>That's the story.</i>

157
00:06:07,325 --> 00:06:08,159
THE SHABBY STATUE GROWS FORGOTTEN

158
00:06:08,535 --> 00:06:10,537
It's a beautiful story.

159
00:06:10,954 --> 00:06:15,083
This is a tale that has been told
for a very long time.

160
00:06:15,166 --> 00:06:18,086
Wisdom from such a long time ago
still applies to this day.

161
00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:20,213
- I was impressed by that.
- Right.

162
00:06:20,630 --> 00:06:23,091
I want to embrace these values myself.

163
00:06:23,174 --> 00:06:24,634
That's why I like to read it.

164
00:06:24,718 --> 00:06:26,303
Right. Oscar Wilde.

165
00:06:26,511 --> 00:06:27,929
- Yes.
- Do you know him?

166
00:06:28,013 --> 00:06:29,598
Yes, I've met him.

167
00:06:30,181 --> 00:06:32,434
I'm a lot like him, you know.

168
00:06:32,517 --> 00:06:34,019
OSCAR WILDE (1854-1900)
I'm "wild" too.

169
00:06:34,436 --> 00:06:35,312
HE LIVED WITH THIS ENERGY FOR 2,000 YEARS

170
00:06:35,395 --> 00:06:36,771
- Wild!
- Right.

171
00:06:37,355 --> 00:06:39,441
What was he like? I'd like to know.

172
00:06:39,524 --> 00:06:40,567
Sorry?

173
00:06:41,234 --> 00:06:43,069
What was Oscar Wilde like?

174
00:06:43,153 --> 00:06:45,822
He also loved making good quotes.

175
00:06:45,906 --> 00:06:47,824
- Quotes.
- Quotes.

176
00:06:48,283 --> 00:06:50,952
- He left some great ones, too.
- Right.

177
00:06:51,286 --> 00:06:52,579
"Be yourself.

178
00:06:53,580 --> 00:06:56,291
Everyone else is already taken."

179
00:06:57,626 --> 00:06:58,543
Have you heard of it before?

180
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:00,837
- "Everyone is already taken."
- Yes.

181
00:07:00,921 --> 00:07:02,631
It means don't try to be someone else.

182
00:07:02,714 --> 00:07:04,633
Don't compare yourself to others.
Be yourself.

183
00:07:05,508 --> 00:07:06,551
Being yourself.

184
00:07:06,635 --> 00:07:08,094
- Right.
- He emphasized authenticity.

185
00:07:08,178 --> 00:07:09,346
- That's right.
- Yes.

186
00:07:09,638 --> 00:07:12,307
What does it mean
to be AKMU, Chan-hyuk, and Su-hyun?

187
00:07:12,390 --> 00:07:13,516
First, to be AKMU.

188
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:15,226
To be AKMU?

189
00:07:15,310 --> 00:07:16,603
WHAT DOES IT MEAN TO BE AKMU?

190
00:07:16,686 --> 00:07:18,313
I think it means to be natural.

191
00:07:18,396 --> 00:07:19,314
Natural.

192
00:07:19,397 --> 00:07:21,691
As we grow up and experience things,

193
00:07:21,775 --> 00:07:24,110
the thoughts that we have
at different ages

194
00:07:24,611 --> 00:07:26,571
are incorporated into our music.

195
00:07:26,947 --> 00:07:29,991
Our first album was called PLAY.

196
00:07:30,075 --> 00:07:32,869
<i>We made it like we were playing,</i>
<i>before we were adults.</i>

197
00:07:32,953 --> 00:07:35,163
<i>Our second album was called Puberty.</i>

198
00:07:35,246 --> 00:07:37,374
<i>We had so many questions about the world.</i>

199
00:07:37,457 --> 00:07:39,292
<i>"Why is this or that like this?"</i>

200
00:07:39,376 --> 00:07:40,919
<i>"It's curious how people move."</i>

201
00:07:41,002 --> 00:07:44,756
<i>And Sailing came out</i>
<i>when I was in my late twenties.</i>

202
00:07:44,839 --> 00:07:47,884
<i>For the first time,</i>
<i>we were experiencing strong emotions.</i>

203
00:07:47,968 --> 00:07:50,053
<i>That album captures that period.</i>

204
00:07:50,136 --> 00:07:53,098
- Your life experiences stack up as songs.
- Yes.

205
00:07:53,181 --> 00:07:55,350
- That's who you are as musicians.
- Yes.

206
00:07:55,433 --> 00:07:57,560
AKMU'S MUSIC IS A RECORD OF THEIR GROWTH
That's our strength.

207
00:07:58,353 --> 00:08:00,105
What does it mean to be Su-hyun?

208
00:08:01,231 --> 00:08:03,900
I can explain that with a song of ours

209
00:08:04,234 --> 00:08:06,486
called "Fry's Dream."

210
00:08:06,736 --> 00:08:09,072
I want to live like a fried egg

211
00:08:09,155 --> 00:08:11,992
lying on top of a bowl of warm rice.

212
00:08:12,075 --> 00:08:13,785
Just relaxing there in the warmth.

213
00:08:14,119 --> 00:08:16,913
I think that explains my nature.

214
00:08:17,330 --> 00:08:19,249
It's something I can't change.

215
00:08:19,541 --> 00:08:20,542
That's just me.

216
00:08:20,959 --> 00:08:22,502
- "Fry's Dream."
- Yes.

217
00:08:23,003 --> 00:08:26,339
- I think what makes Su-hyun herself
- Yes?

218
00:08:27,132 --> 00:08:29,968
is that she's just someone
born to be loved.

219
00:08:30,844 --> 00:08:34,097
<i>Whatever she says, everyone loves it.</i>

220
00:08:34,180 --> 00:08:35,181
<i>Everyone adores her.</i>

221
00:08:35,265 --> 00:08:37,642
SHE'S SOMEONE WHO'S ALWAYS LOVED

222
00:08:37,726 --> 00:08:40,395
You're not just a princess.
You were born a princess.

223
00:08:40,770 --> 00:08:42,230
You were born lovable.

224
00:08:43,148 --> 00:08:44,232
You are extraordinary.

225
00:08:46,901 --> 00:08:48,862
FAINTING FROM HER LOVELINESS

226
00:08:52,532 --> 00:08:54,492
He speaks English really well.

227
00:08:54,576 --> 00:08:56,327
- Of course! He's 2,000 years old.
- True.

228
00:08:56,411 --> 00:08:58,830
You must speak every language well.

229
00:08:59,831 --> 00:09:00,665
Wow, really?

230
00:09:00,749 --> 00:09:01,583
SPANISH FOR "HELLO"
<i>Hola.</i>

231
00:09:01,666 --> 00:09:02,959
- <i>Hola!</i>
- <i>Bonjour.</i>

232
00:09:03,043 --> 00:09:04,210
FRENCH FOR "HELLO"

233
00:09:04,294 --> 00:09:05,295
MONGOLIAN FOR "HELLO"
<i>Sain baina uu?</i>

234
00:09:05,378 --> 00:09:07,422
Wow, you speak Mongolian too.

235
00:09:07,714 --> 00:09:08,798
<i>Sain baina uu?</i>

236
00:09:09,841 --> 00:09:12,719
Now, before we set a price
for the book, <i>The Happy Prince</i>,

237
00:09:12,802 --> 00:09:15,180
I, Hocrates, the man who asks questions,

238
00:09:15,263 --> 00:09:18,850
will ask some questions about AKMU's life.

239
00:09:20,435 --> 00:09:21,311
Yeah.

240
00:09:22,103 --> 00:09:24,814
Akdong Musician started in Mongolia.

241
00:09:25,398 --> 00:09:28,443
When did you move to Mongolia
with your parents?

242
00:09:29,736 --> 00:09:33,073
When I was in sixth grade
and she was in third grade.

243
00:09:33,156 --> 00:09:36,910
Our parents went to Mongolia
as missionaries.

244
00:09:36,993 --> 00:09:37,869
<i>I see.</i>

245
00:09:37,952 --> 00:09:40,497
<i>We didn't know the details at the time.</i>

246
00:09:40,580 --> 00:09:43,458
<i>I was just excited</i>
<i>about living and studying abroad.</i>

247
00:09:43,541 --> 00:09:44,375
<i>Right.</i>

248
00:09:44,459 --> 00:09:45,293
You remember that?

249
00:09:45,376 --> 00:09:47,337
- Of course.
- We thought it was for our studies.

250
00:09:47,420 --> 00:09:50,006
<i>I remember thinking,</i>
<i>"We're studying abroad!"</i>

251
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:52,008
Mongolia is big.

252
00:09:52,092 --> 00:09:53,718
- Yes, it is.
- Right?

253
00:09:53,927 --> 00:09:55,428
Where in Mongolia did you live?

254
00:09:55,512 --> 00:09:58,098
We were in the capital, Ulaanbaatar.

255
00:09:58,473 --> 00:09:59,974
<i>Yes, Mongolia is big,</i>

256
00:10:00,058 --> 00:10:03,686
<i>but most of the people</i>
<i>live in Ulaanbaatar.</i>

257
00:10:04,312 --> 00:10:06,564
<i>Outside of the city, it's just plains.</i>

258
00:10:06,648 --> 00:10:08,691
<i>- That's most of the country.</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

259
00:10:08,775 --> 00:10:12,070
- It must've been hard to adapt.
- Right.

260
00:10:12,153 --> 00:10:14,656
- You couldn't speak the language.
- That's right.

261
00:10:14,739 --> 00:10:17,158
Did you have a hard time communicating?

262
00:10:17,659 --> 00:10:19,994
We mostly communicated in English.

263
00:10:20,078 --> 00:10:22,122
- I see.
- But even with English,

264
00:10:22,205 --> 00:10:23,957
all we'd learned

265
00:10:24,040 --> 00:10:26,835
in English class back in Korea

266
00:10:26,918 --> 00:10:28,795
ZEETO WAS AN ALIEN CHARACTER
was, "Hello, Zeeto, hello."

267
00:10:28,878 --> 00:10:30,421
IN ELEMENTARY ENGLISH TEXTBOOKS
That was all.

268
00:10:30,505 --> 00:10:32,674
- But when we got there--
- It was advanced.

269
00:10:32,757 --> 00:10:35,009
They were like,
"What's going on? Blah blah."

270
00:10:36,177 --> 00:10:37,929
And we were like, "What?"

271
00:10:38,388 --> 00:10:41,015
"Why is it different
from what we've learned?"

272
00:10:41,724 --> 00:10:42,642
It went like that.

273
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:44,978
I see.

274
00:10:45,770 --> 00:10:47,188
Did it go like that for you?

275
00:10:47,689 --> 00:10:49,440
When I was a kid,

276
00:10:50,066 --> 00:10:51,818
I didn't talk much.

277
00:10:52,110 --> 00:10:55,196
Also, I couldn't confidently do
something I was bad at.

278
00:10:55,280 --> 00:10:57,323
She was always confident,

279
00:10:57,407 --> 00:11:00,702
but I wanted it to be perfect
in my head before I said it.

280
00:11:00,785 --> 00:11:03,121
Do you know what I mean? I was like that.

281
00:11:03,496 --> 00:11:05,415
- That's how it was for me.
- This is what was so annoying.

282
00:11:05,999 --> 00:11:10,003
For example,
I was talking to a shop employee.

283
00:11:10,461 --> 00:11:12,130
I wanted to try to talk to them,

284
00:11:12,213 --> 00:11:13,715
so I ordered for myself.

285
00:11:14,174 --> 00:11:15,383
My English was bad,

286
00:11:15,466 --> 00:11:19,554
but I just said something like,
"I want... coffee."

287
00:11:19,637 --> 00:11:21,097
He didn't say a thing.

288
00:11:21,389 --> 00:11:23,975
I said "Thank you,"
and was leaving happily.

289
00:11:24,058 --> 00:11:25,393
And he whispered to me,

290
00:11:25,476 --> 00:11:27,312
"Your grammar was wrong."

291
00:11:27,395 --> 00:11:28,646
He said that to me.

292
00:11:28,771 --> 00:11:31,316
"It would've been better
if you said it like this."

293
00:11:31,441 --> 00:11:33,067
He was always like that.

294
00:11:33,943 --> 00:11:34,819
Like a director?

295
00:11:35,278 --> 00:11:36,571
He couldn't speak,

296
00:11:36,779 --> 00:11:38,698
but he could analyze it in his head.

297
00:11:38,781 --> 00:11:40,700
- That's right.
- He'd always be like that.

298
00:11:40,783 --> 00:11:42,827
Because he's older,

299
00:11:42,911 --> 00:11:44,621
- he was on a higher level.
- Yes.

300
00:11:44,704 --> 00:11:46,080
But because of this personality,

301
00:11:46,539 --> 00:11:48,791
- even though he knew plenty,
- Right.

302
00:11:48,875 --> 00:11:51,294
- he couldn't confidently speak up.
- No.

303
00:11:51,377 --> 00:11:54,297
But even though you were like that,

304
00:11:54,380 --> 00:11:55,798
you had a lot of friends?

305
00:11:56,549 --> 00:11:58,176
That was a different issue.

306
00:11:58,301 --> 00:11:59,928
I was kind of

307
00:12:00,178 --> 00:12:01,471
an attention seeker at the time.

308
00:12:02,096 --> 00:12:05,808
One time, everyone was
eating together after church.

309
00:12:06,100 --> 00:12:09,229
And he quietly went up to the front.

310
00:12:09,479 --> 00:12:11,981
I was like, "What's he doing?
That's not like him."

311
00:12:12,065 --> 00:12:13,441
He held the mic and said...

312
00:12:14,984 --> 00:12:16,444
"Diarrhea."

313
00:12:16,778 --> 00:12:17,654
Diarrhea?

314
00:12:17,737 --> 00:12:19,822
Everyone was eating curry.

315
00:12:20,323 --> 00:12:22,909
"Excuse me while you're eating. Diarrhea."

316
00:12:22,992 --> 00:12:24,202
Then, he left.

317
00:12:24,869 --> 00:12:27,038
So everyone was like...

318
00:12:27,789 --> 00:12:28,915
"What was that?"

319
00:12:28,998 --> 00:12:32,543
Some people we were close to
were booing him.

320
00:12:32,710 --> 00:12:33,711
I was like...

321
00:12:35,838 --> 00:12:37,465
"What?" Like that.

322
00:12:38,091 --> 00:12:39,342
I liked stuff like that.

323
00:12:39,425 --> 00:12:40,677
- How people would react.
- He likes how people react?

324
00:12:40,760 --> 00:12:42,387
- No matter the reaction,
- Yes?

325
00:12:42,804 --> 00:12:44,806
- good or bad.
- Even reacting badly.

326
00:12:44,889 --> 00:12:47,016
Creating a stir.

327
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:48,476
It was a sign of my influence.

328
00:12:49,477 --> 00:12:50,603
If you think about it.

329
00:12:50,687 --> 00:12:52,230
HE STIRRED THINGS UP AS HE WANTED

330
00:12:52,313 --> 00:12:54,649
All I said were two things,

331
00:12:54,857 --> 00:12:57,777
- and everyone went wild.
- "What's he doing?"

332
00:12:57,860 --> 00:13:00,613
I enjoyed that as a kid.

333
00:13:00,905 --> 00:13:02,365
He didn't say much,

334
00:13:02,448 --> 00:13:05,326
- but he sure did some unusual things.
- I tried to.

335
00:13:05,785 --> 00:13:08,579
I DON'T KNOW WHO I AM...

336
00:13:08,663 --> 00:13:11,666
DON'T LOOK AT ME LIKE THAT
I'M A <i>SHI BOE</i>

337
00:13:11,749 --> 00:13:13,835
I'M NOT CRYING BECAUSE I LOST,
I'M STRONG ENOUGH TO KNOW WHEN TO GIVE IN

338
00:13:13,918 --> 00:13:16,421
A BOY WHO SEEKED ATTENTION ONLINE
14 YEARS AGO

339
00:13:16,796 --> 00:13:18,006
What about your outfits?

340
00:13:18,381 --> 00:13:20,216
Oh, I wore my mom's clothes.

341
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:22,719
CHAN-HYUK WEARING HIS MOM'S SUNGLASSES

342
00:13:22,802 --> 00:13:24,971
- I did.
- That's right.

343
00:13:25,054 --> 00:13:26,347
I wore my mom's coat.

344
00:13:26,431 --> 00:13:28,516
It was white with a fur collar.

345
00:13:28,599 --> 00:13:29,600
- Right.
- My gosh.

346
00:13:29,684 --> 00:13:31,019
- Things like that.
- Yes.

347
00:13:31,102 --> 00:13:32,186
And I wore her shoes.

348
00:13:32,353 --> 00:13:33,688
UNBELIEVABLE
Right.

349
00:13:33,813 --> 00:13:34,856
Did they even fit?

350
00:13:34,939 --> 00:13:36,190
They didn't.

351
00:13:36,274 --> 00:13:38,026
I squished my toes in there.

352
00:13:40,194 --> 00:13:41,529
I wanted to wear something different.

353
00:13:41,612 --> 00:13:43,865
That's right!

354
00:13:44,615 --> 00:13:45,575
I forgot about it.

355
00:13:45,658 --> 00:13:46,951
SQUISHED YOUR TOES LIKE THIS

356
00:13:47,952 --> 00:13:49,495
IN STITCHES
I remember.

357
00:13:49,579 --> 00:13:51,205
- He was unique.
- Yes.

358
00:13:51,289 --> 00:13:53,458
You can already tell from these stories.

359
00:13:53,875 --> 00:13:56,461
That could've made your sister
a bit uncomfortable.

360
00:13:57,045 --> 00:13:58,504
You could've embarrassed her.

361
00:13:59,339 --> 00:14:01,758
- I don't think he cared about that.
- No.

362
00:14:01,841 --> 00:14:02,800
I've

363
00:14:03,217 --> 00:14:04,552
never considered that.

364
00:14:04,635 --> 00:14:05,887
Not ever.

365
00:14:06,512 --> 00:14:09,057
- "I'll embarrass her."
- What a fresh perspective.

366
00:14:09,140 --> 00:14:10,350
I see.

367
00:14:10,725 --> 00:14:13,478
My consistent attitude
of "Why is he like this?"

368
00:14:13,561 --> 00:14:14,896
started back then.

369
00:14:14,979 --> 00:14:17,148
- Were any of your friends into him?
- No.

370
00:14:17,231 --> 00:14:18,441
No, never.

371
00:14:18,524 --> 00:14:19,984
- Maybe at least one?
- No.

372
00:14:20,068 --> 00:14:22,653
Was there anyone
who was a little bit interested?

373
00:14:22,737 --> 00:14:23,905
No, there was no one.

374
00:14:24,072 --> 00:14:25,156
No one at all?

375
00:14:26,366 --> 00:14:27,325
I think we can move on.

376
00:14:28,785 --> 00:14:30,161
Let's move on, then.

377
00:14:32,538 --> 00:14:34,749
WOULD YOU LIKE TO WALK WITH ME?

378
00:14:34,832 --> 00:14:38,503
WOULD YOU LIKE TO WALK HAND IN HAND
BEYOND THE TWINKLING GALAXY?

379
00:14:39,128 --> 00:14:40,713
You took a long break

380
00:14:40,797 --> 00:14:42,048
- after a year of school.
- Right.

381
00:14:42,131 --> 00:14:43,633
- You were homeschooled.
- Yes.

382
00:14:43,716 --> 00:14:46,427
There was a change
in your learning environment.

383
00:14:46,511 --> 00:14:49,722
Every kid says,
"I don't want to go to school.

384
00:14:49,806 --> 00:14:52,016
I don't want to study or do homework."

385
00:14:52,141 --> 00:14:54,227
I was like that, just like everyone else.

386
00:14:54,310 --> 00:14:57,897
One day, our dad said,
"Do you guys want to try homeschooling?

387
00:14:58,022 --> 00:14:59,524
No need to go to school."

388
00:14:59,607 --> 00:15:00,942
When he said that,

389
00:15:01,359 --> 00:15:03,277
I was so happy. I told all my friends,

390
00:15:03,361 --> 00:15:06,030
"I don't have to study anymore.
I'm going to play."

391
00:15:06,280 --> 00:15:08,866
Everyone was jealous
when we started homeschooling.

392
00:15:08,950 --> 00:15:11,411
<i>- It was your dad's idea.</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

393
00:15:11,494 --> 00:15:12,745
But it turned out

394
00:15:13,162 --> 00:15:15,248
that it was the same thing as school,

395
00:15:15,331 --> 00:15:18,042
but we were just doing it at home.

396
00:15:18,126 --> 00:15:20,044
- And without our friends.
- Right.

397
00:15:20,962 --> 00:15:22,547
IT WASN'T WHAT THEY EXPECTED
<i>It was even harder.</i>

398
00:15:22,630 --> 00:15:23,464
<i>- Definitely.</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

399
00:15:23,548 --> 00:15:26,175
<i>We had to be in the living room at 6 a.m.</i>

400
00:15:26,259 --> 00:15:28,177
- We did.
- You must've missed school.

401
00:15:28,261 --> 00:15:29,762
We did miss school.

402
00:15:29,846 --> 00:15:32,807
But the real reason
why we couldn't go to school

403
00:15:33,724 --> 00:15:38,146
was our financial situation.

404
00:15:39,063 --> 00:15:43,484
The school there wasn't free.
We had to pay.

405
00:15:43,568 --> 00:15:44,485
- I see.
- Yes.

406
00:15:44,569 --> 00:15:46,612
So we had no choice.

407
00:15:46,779 --> 00:15:49,949
But you couldn't have known at the time.

408
00:15:50,074 --> 00:15:52,160
We figured it out on our own.

409
00:15:52,243 --> 00:15:53,744
What was on the table changed.

410
00:15:54,162 --> 00:15:55,329
- Our meals.
- Right.

411
00:15:55,455 --> 00:15:58,207
We kept the lights off
to cut down on electricity bills.

412
00:15:58,708 --> 00:16:01,544
We guessed from things like that.

413
00:16:01,627 --> 00:16:04,881
We were already
old enough for middle school.

414
00:16:06,340 --> 00:16:08,259
We were homeschooled for a year.

415
00:16:08,342 --> 00:16:10,136
And then, everyone realized

416
00:16:10,219 --> 00:16:11,345
that it didn't work.

417
00:16:11,679 --> 00:16:17,602
"We can't bring the same system as school
into homeschooling."

418
00:16:17,685 --> 00:16:19,937
Everyone in our family realized that.

419
00:16:20,313 --> 00:16:21,898
So that's when we decided.

420
00:16:23,149 --> 00:16:25,610
"You don't have to study."
That was our parents' decision.

421
00:16:26,277 --> 00:16:27,612
"You don't have to study.

422
00:16:27,695 --> 00:16:29,947
Instead, do whatever you want."

423
00:16:30,698 --> 00:16:33,618
Right after that decision,

424
00:16:34,911 --> 00:16:36,120
we started making music.

425
00:16:38,039 --> 00:16:40,208
Your parents were very bold.

426
00:16:41,501 --> 00:16:44,212
Were you always kind of into music?

427
00:16:44,629 --> 00:16:46,380
We were so bored.

428
00:16:46,631 --> 00:16:48,049
- There was nothing to do.
- Right.

429
00:16:48,132 --> 00:16:51,969
<i>We didn't have any friends our age.</i>

430
00:16:52,053 --> 00:16:54,931
<i>We didn't have</i>
<i>access to the Internet at home.</i>

431
00:16:55,014 --> 00:16:58,309
When the electricity was on at home,

432
00:16:58,392 --> 00:16:59,602
we could play the piano.

433
00:16:59,685 --> 00:17:02,230
And even without electricity,
we had the guitar.

434
00:17:02,813 --> 00:17:05,358
That's when Chan-hyuk
started playing the guitar

435
00:17:05,441 --> 00:17:07,777
<i>and I started playing the piano.</i>

436
00:17:07,860 --> 00:17:09,820
<i>I always loved to sing.</i>

437
00:17:09,904 --> 00:17:12,073
- Music was how you had fun.
- That's right.

438
00:17:12,156 --> 00:17:14,408
- That's how we had fun.
- It was the only thing you could do.

439
00:17:14,742 --> 00:17:17,787
Did you already know
how to play instruments?

440
00:17:18,412 --> 00:17:19,872
Just the basics.

441
00:17:19,956 --> 00:17:22,833
- We both knew just the basic chords.
- I see.

442
00:17:22,917 --> 00:17:25,461
- You didn't take courses.
- No.

443
00:17:26,087 --> 00:17:28,839
People always complimented Su-hyun
for her singing.

444
00:17:28,923 --> 00:17:30,883
<i>She was confident on top of that,</i>

445
00:17:30,967 --> 00:17:33,803
<i>so everyone said,</i>
<i>"You're a fantastic singer."</i>

446
00:17:33,886 --> 00:17:37,640
"You should be a musician."
She'd heard that since she was little.

447
00:17:38,099 --> 00:17:40,101
That's why at the time,

448
00:17:40,476 --> 00:17:42,019
I wanted to be a singer.

449
00:17:42,103 --> 00:17:44,772
My dream was very clear.

450
00:17:44,855 --> 00:17:48,067
- But Chan-hyuk had absolutely no idea.
- I didn't.

451
00:17:48,317 --> 00:17:50,653
Even now, it's surreal.

452
00:17:51,654 --> 00:17:54,740
I had zero talent in songwriting.

453
00:17:54,865 --> 00:17:59,203
Before I wrote
my first official original song,

454
00:17:59,287 --> 00:18:02,456
there was
my first unofficial original song.

455
00:18:02,623 --> 00:18:05,459
I must've really liked feces at the time.

456
00:18:06,085 --> 00:18:08,337
It was just a list of types of feces.

457
00:18:09,463 --> 00:18:10,756
That was the first song.

458
00:18:11,382 --> 00:18:13,426
It went like, "This poop, that poop."

459
00:18:13,509 --> 00:18:14,385
SHOCKED, DISGUSTED, CALM

460
00:18:14,468 --> 00:18:16,637
I must've really liked that at the time.

461
00:18:16,721 --> 00:18:17,597
What?

462
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:18,931
- I just had a song like that.
- Oh my gosh!

463
00:18:19,098 --> 00:18:20,433
I sang it and thought,

464
00:18:20,516 --> 00:18:22,059
"Songwriting is not for me."

465
00:18:22,852 --> 00:18:25,313
Yes. Months earlier,

466
00:18:25,396 --> 00:18:27,148
I'd realized that I had no talent.

467
00:18:27,231 --> 00:18:29,317
Not just poop, but diarrhea, and so on?

468
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:31,485
- Yes, loose stool--
- Wait, I remember!

469
00:18:31,569 --> 00:18:33,070
- I don't want to.
- That's it.

470
00:18:33,404 --> 00:18:35,406
This has never been revealed before.

471
00:18:35,489 --> 00:18:36,532
FORCED TO RECALL THAT SHARED MEMORY
Right.

472
00:18:36,616 --> 00:18:39,285
That's why I think
my skills were learned, not innate.

473
00:18:39,785 --> 00:18:41,871
Before I wrote songs
that showed potential,

474
00:18:41,996 --> 00:18:44,123
I wrote a song like that.

475
00:18:44,206 --> 00:18:47,126
And I thought to myself,
"I don't have musical talent."

476
00:18:47,627 --> 00:18:49,337
But one day at church,

477
00:18:49,587 --> 00:18:52,506
a friend made a song called "iPod."

478
00:18:52,590 --> 00:18:53,716
- "iPod"?
- Yes, "iPod."

479
00:18:53,799 --> 00:18:56,093
- That was when the iPod just came out.
- Right.

480
00:18:56,177 --> 00:18:57,511
POPULAR MP3 PLAYER FROM APPLE
The first and second ones.

481
00:18:57,595 --> 00:18:59,180
- From Apple.
- Yes.

482
00:18:59,263 --> 00:19:01,557
- They were very popular.
- Yes.

483
00:19:01,766 --> 00:19:03,392
When we went to church,

484
00:19:03,476 --> 00:19:04,810
everyone was singing it.

485
00:19:04,894 --> 00:19:06,771
THE SONG BECAME POPULAR AMONG FRIENDS

486
00:19:07,146 --> 00:19:09,732
And you know me. I had to outdo that.

487
00:19:10,858 --> 00:19:11,817
"iPod"?

488
00:19:11,901 --> 00:19:13,069
"I'll do Galaxy."

489
00:19:15,363 --> 00:19:16,614
That's how it happened.

490
00:19:16,906 --> 00:19:19,075
- "Apple? I'll do Samsung."
- Yes.

491
00:19:20,826 --> 00:19:22,662
- To go against it.
- Yes.

492
00:19:22,745 --> 00:19:24,205
ATTENTION-SEEKING WITH ADDED PATRIOTISM

493
00:19:24,288 --> 00:19:25,373
- As a Korean.
- Really?

494
00:19:25,456 --> 00:19:26,290
Really.

495
00:19:26,457 --> 00:19:27,917
But here's the thing.

496
00:19:28,250 --> 00:19:30,503
If we were doing Apple versus Samsung,

497
00:19:30,586 --> 00:19:33,923
I thought I had to level up my game.

498
00:19:34,006 --> 00:19:35,424
That's what I thought.

499
00:19:35,508 --> 00:19:39,512
So I looked up
the definition of the word "galaxy"

500
00:19:39,595 --> 00:19:41,889
- and learned what it meant.
- A group of stars.

501
00:19:41,972 --> 00:19:46,435
So I decided to incorporate that meaning
into a song called "Galaxy."

502
00:19:46,519 --> 00:19:48,062
Unfortunately,

503
00:19:48,312 --> 00:19:50,731
- it wasn't so popular at church.
- No.

504
00:19:50,981 --> 00:19:54,276
But we wanted to sing it for our parents.

505
00:19:54,360 --> 00:19:56,404
So we did on that day,

506
00:19:56,821 --> 00:19:58,072
and they loved it.

507
00:19:59,031 --> 00:20:00,032
"What is this?"

508
00:20:00,116 --> 00:20:02,284
They saw that it was more than a hobby.

509
00:20:02,368 --> 00:20:04,078
- They realized that.
- Yes.

510
00:20:04,161 --> 00:20:06,455
- You were on another level.
- Yes.

511
00:20:06,539 --> 00:20:07,998
And their kids

512
00:20:08,082 --> 00:20:11,168
wrote this unheard-of song

513
00:20:11,252 --> 00:20:13,754
and sang it together in front of them.

514
00:20:13,838 --> 00:20:15,047
That surprised them.

515
00:20:15,131 --> 00:20:18,008
- Your parents gave you
- Right.

516
00:20:18,092 --> 00:20:20,469
- a sincere compliment.
- That's right.

517
00:20:20,553 --> 00:20:22,430
- That gives you confidence.
- Yes.

518
00:20:22,513 --> 00:20:24,098
- Yes.
- That's so important.

519
00:20:24,181 --> 00:20:26,183
With that confidence, I went to my room

520
00:20:26,267 --> 00:20:28,060
- and wrote another song.
- He did.

521
00:20:28,144 --> 00:20:30,312
The next day, I wrote a couple more.

522
00:20:30,396 --> 00:20:32,398
The day after that, I wrote even more.

523
00:20:32,481 --> 00:20:33,441
That's right.

524
00:20:33,524 --> 00:20:35,401
- I had an explosion of creativity.
- He was addicted.

525
00:20:35,484 --> 00:20:36,694
- Thanks to your parents.
- Yes.

526
00:20:36,777 --> 00:20:38,821
- Yes.
- It was like an explosion. Boom.

527
00:20:39,280 --> 00:20:40,364
"I'm good at this."

528
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:42,450
- "I found it."
- Right.

529
00:20:42,533 --> 00:20:47,371
I think what made
his potential break through

530
00:20:47,455 --> 00:20:48,456
was recognition.

531
00:20:48,998 --> 00:20:50,708
For the first time,

532
00:20:50,791 --> 00:20:53,878
- he received genuine recognition.
- That's right.

533
00:20:53,961 --> 00:20:57,173
That made him realize his potential,
and it started to come out.

534
00:20:57,256 --> 00:20:59,967
Who knows, when I made my first song,

535
00:21:00,050 --> 00:21:01,260
if my parents just said,

536
00:21:01,343 --> 00:21:03,387
"Well..."

537
00:21:03,512 --> 00:21:05,931
- "It's good."
- "It's good," or something like that,

538
00:21:06,015 --> 00:21:09,101
I might not have run to my room
and written another song.

539
00:21:09,894 --> 00:21:12,813
Your parents became your number one fans.

540
00:21:12,897 --> 00:21:14,440
<i>They posted videos on YouTube</i>

541
00:21:14,523 --> 00:21:16,150
<i>- and documented everything.</i>
<i>- Right.</i>

542
00:21:16,233 --> 00:21:18,903
<i>- A lot of people liked and supported you.</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

543
00:21:18,986 --> 00:21:24,241
THEIR PARENTS POSTED

544
00:21:24,325 --> 00:21:29,497
THEIR ORIGINAL SONG "GALAXY" ON YOUTUBE

545
00:21:29,580 --> 00:21:30,956
That gave you confidence,

546
00:21:31,040 --> 00:21:33,459
and that confidence pushed you forward.

547
00:21:33,542 --> 00:21:35,336
I have no words.

548
00:21:35,419 --> 00:21:36,754
What's more amazing

549
00:21:36,837 --> 00:21:38,506
is that I wrote "Galaxy"

550
00:21:38,589 --> 00:21:40,216
- in January,
- I see.

551
00:21:40,299 --> 00:21:43,219
and in that same year,
we were on <i>K-pop Star</i>.

552
00:21:43,344 --> 00:21:44,845
- We did.
- Yes.

553
00:21:45,971 --> 00:21:48,766
- I think that's the amazing part.
- Yes.

554
00:21:49,016 --> 00:21:51,977
Akdong Musician became K-pop stars.

555
00:21:52,478 --> 00:21:54,647
What made you audition for <i>K-pop Star?</i>

556
00:21:55,523 --> 00:21:56,690
Someone contacted us.

557
00:21:56,941 --> 00:21:58,776
Because of a visa issue,

558
00:21:58,859 --> 00:22:00,945
the family was in Korea for a few months.

559
00:22:01,320 --> 00:22:03,656
And we had nothing to do during that time.

560
00:22:03,781 --> 00:22:05,908
- So we made songs as usual
- Right.

561
00:22:05,991 --> 00:22:08,118
and posted videos online.

562
00:22:08,202 --> 00:22:10,996
- Right.
- We just kept doing that.

563
00:22:11,080 --> 00:22:12,164
People saw that,

564
00:22:12,706 --> 00:22:14,875
and the first show that contacted us

565
00:22:15,376 --> 00:22:16,418
was <i>Star King</i>.

566
00:22:17,962 --> 00:22:18,963
That's right.

567
00:22:19,839 --> 00:22:21,340
THEY WERE FATED TO MEET HOCRATES
That's right!

568
00:22:21,423 --> 00:22:22,758
That's crazy.

569
00:22:23,342 --> 00:22:24,218
Right.

570
00:22:24,301 --> 00:22:26,720
I was the host, so I would know.

571
00:22:26,887 --> 00:22:28,472
ONE OF THE FEW MEMORIES HE'S SURE ABOUT
Wait a minute.

572
00:22:28,556 --> 00:22:30,641
- But you were never on <i>Star King</i>.
- No.

573
00:22:30,724 --> 00:22:31,851
Why not?

574
00:22:32,059 --> 00:22:34,645
Because we had to
go back to Mongolia soon.

575
00:22:35,020 --> 00:22:37,857
So we weren't sure

576
00:22:37,940 --> 00:22:40,943
- I see.
- if it was the right thing to do.

577
00:22:41,443 --> 00:22:43,237
We decided not to do it

578
00:22:43,320 --> 00:22:45,948
and rejected any other shows, too.

579
00:22:46,532 --> 00:22:51,537
Then, <i>K-pop Star</i> contacted us.

580
00:22:51,704 --> 00:22:52,997
What about <i>Star King?</i>

581
00:22:53,080 --> 00:22:54,790
HE WANTS TO KNOW SINCE IT'S
ONE OF THE FEW MEMORIES HE'S SURE ABOUT

582
00:22:54,874 --> 00:22:56,834
From what I can remember,

583
00:22:56,917 --> 00:22:58,711
we rejected everything,

584
00:22:58,794 --> 00:23:00,212
but if by any chance,

585
00:23:00,296 --> 00:23:03,757
<i>K-pop Star</i> contacted us again,

586
00:23:03,924 --> 00:23:06,760
we said we'd consider doing it.

587
00:23:06,969 --> 00:23:09,013
And they actually did.

588
00:23:09,096 --> 00:23:10,598
- They didn't give up.
- No.

589
00:23:10,681 --> 00:23:13,601
They contacted us
and asked if we'd reconsider.

590
00:23:13,684 --> 00:23:14,852
That's when we thought

591
00:23:14,935 --> 00:23:16,520
we should do it.

592
00:23:16,604 --> 00:23:17,938
That's how we joined it.

593
00:23:18,022 --> 00:23:19,565
- Maybe it was fate.
- Exactly.

594
00:23:19,648 --> 00:23:22,526
Our visa issue was still unsolved anyway.

595
00:23:22,693 --> 00:23:26,196
We just wanted to give it a try.

596
00:23:26,280 --> 00:23:27,781
We were going to go back

597
00:23:27,865 --> 00:23:29,867
once the issue was solved.

598
00:23:30,075 --> 00:23:32,703
But we kept surviving each round.

599
00:23:32,786 --> 00:23:34,580
It just kept going.

600
00:23:34,830 --> 00:23:37,416
When the issue was solved
and we had to go back,

601
00:23:37,499 --> 00:23:39,793
our parents asked us what we wanted to do.

602
00:23:39,877 --> 00:23:41,545
- We said we'd keep going.
- We were having fun,

603
00:23:41,629 --> 00:23:43,255
so we wanted to keep going.

604
00:23:43,339 --> 00:23:45,925
So our parents went to Mongolia first,

605
00:23:46,008 --> 00:23:49,595
and we stayed with our grandmother
to keep going.

606
00:23:52,640 --> 00:23:54,141
So, you went on the show.

607
00:23:54,224 --> 00:23:55,643
At some point,

608
00:23:55,809 --> 00:23:57,937
- when you think there might be a chance,
- Yes.

609
00:23:58,020 --> 00:24:01,315
that's when the pressure sets in.

610
00:24:01,398 --> 00:24:02,358
- Right.
- I see.

611
00:24:02,566 --> 00:24:04,652
Wasn't the competition a lot of pressure?

612
00:24:05,235 --> 00:24:06,862
We knew nothing at the time.

613
00:24:06,946 --> 00:24:08,489
- Nothing.
- Yes.

614
00:24:08,572 --> 00:24:09,782
- We were too young.
- Right.

615
00:24:10,199 --> 00:24:13,535
It was our first time
experiencing society.

616
00:24:13,661 --> 00:24:17,331
We'd never been away
from our parents our whole lives,

617
00:24:17,414 --> 00:24:18,958
but we were.

618
00:24:19,291 --> 00:24:21,961
And we were thrown into a competition.

619
00:24:22,127 --> 00:24:24,463
We were there for months.

620
00:24:24,672 --> 00:24:29,635
It was just me and Su-hyun,
without our parents.

621
00:24:30,052 --> 00:24:33,973
SIBLINGS RELYING ON EACH OTHER
The weight of responsibility was huge.

622
00:24:34,056 --> 00:24:37,017
I didn't realize back then,
but looking back now,

623
00:24:37,101 --> 00:24:39,937
I think I tried
to play the role of a parent.

624
00:24:42,314 --> 00:24:44,066
I just remembered something.

625
00:24:44,149 --> 00:24:46,235
You might not want me mentioning this.

626
00:24:46,777 --> 00:24:48,404
During the auditions,

627
00:24:48,487 --> 00:24:50,489
when we were closer to the end,

628
00:24:50,781 --> 00:24:53,534
he had to keep writing songs.

629
00:24:53,617 --> 00:24:55,077
Oh, it's that story. I remember.

630
00:24:55,160 --> 00:24:56,453
Do you remember?

631
00:24:56,745 --> 00:24:59,123
He was in the small room in the corner,

632
00:24:59,206 --> 00:25:01,834
writing songs all night.

633
00:25:01,917 --> 00:25:04,294
I slept really well that night,

634
00:25:04,378 --> 00:25:07,214
and when I woke up,
I was like, "Where is he?"

635
00:25:07,297 --> 00:25:10,134
I realized he didn't sleep
and opened the door.

636
00:25:10,217 --> 00:25:13,512
He was sitting on the floor
with this guitar, looking worn out.

637
00:25:14,346 --> 00:25:16,473
He was like, "Are you up?"

638
00:25:16,557 --> 00:25:18,767
I asked him if he hadn't slept.

639
00:25:18,851 --> 00:25:20,602
He told me he stayed up writing.

640
00:25:20,686 --> 00:25:22,813
I told him to rest, and he was like,

641
00:25:23,397 --> 00:25:26,692
"Hey, can you make me
some instant noodles?"

642
00:25:26,859 --> 00:25:28,819
I was well-rested, by the way.

643
00:25:28,902 --> 00:25:30,529
I was in a good mood.

644
00:25:30,612 --> 00:25:32,656
So when he asked me to do that,

645
00:25:32,740 --> 00:25:34,116
I was pouting.

646
00:25:34,199 --> 00:25:36,744
I was like, "Go make it yourself!"

647
00:25:37,327 --> 00:25:39,329
SU-HYUN JOKED AS USUAL
"I don't want to! You do it."

648
00:25:39,413 --> 00:25:41,623
And then, he was suddenly like,

649
00:25:42,416 --> 00:25:44,960
"Why can't you just make me some noodles?"

650
00:25:45,044 --> 00:25:46,378
He yelled at me

651
00:25:46,462 --> 00:25:48,047
and started bawling.

652
00:25:48,297 --> 00:25:51,717
- I was absolutely shocked
- I did do all of that.

653
00:25:51,800 --> 00:25:53,761
and went, "Sorry, I will."

654
00:25:54,678 --> 00:25:57,473
Then I ran to the kitchen

655
00:25:57,556 --> 00:25:59,808
and made him those noodles.

656
00:25:59,892 --> 00:26:01,602
But he was crying for a while.

657
00:26:01,685 --> 00:26:03,062
He didn't stop.

658
00:26:03,145 --> 00:26:04,313
That's when I realized

659
00:26:04,646 --> 00:26:07,232
- that he had a lot going on.
- I forgot about that.

660
00:26:07,316 --> 00:26:08,150
Right?

661
00:26:08,233 --> 00:26:10,611
He'd been so stressed

662
00:26:10,986 --> 00:26:12,988
taking care of things for me.

663
00:26:13,072 --> 00:26:15,032
- That's when I realized that.
- Right.

664
00:26:15,115 --> 00:26:18,494
- I was young, and everything had changed.
- Right.

665
00:26:18,577 --> 00:26:21,330
It was pretty much like the last straw

666
00:26:21,663 --> 00:26:22,998
that broke the camel's back.

667
00:26:23,791 --> 00:26:24,750
I would've been
in my first year of high school.

668
00:26:24,833 --> 00:26:26,543
All that weight on your shoulders.

669
00:26:26,627 --> 00:26:28,128
- Yes.
- I was acting foolishly.

670
00:26:28,504 --> 00:26:29,755
Over some instant noodles.

671
00:26:29,838 --> 00:26:30,923
It was over some noodles.

672
00:26:31,006 --> 00:26:32,382
"Can you make me some noodles?"

673
00:26:32,466 --> 00:26:33,675
SHE WOULDN'T HAVE KNOWN IF SHE DID AS TOLD

674
00:26:34,384 --> 00:26:37,054
After going through that tough time,

675
00:26:37,304 --> 00:26:39,014
Akdong Musician

676
00:26:39,848 --> 00:26:42,226
finally won the trophy.

677
00:26:42,309 --> 00:26:43,727
- Yes.
- Yes.

678
00:26:44,019 --> 00:26:46,230
And your debut album was a huge hit.

679
00:26:46,730 --> 00:26:49,316
- Not 100%, but "200%."
- Yes.

680
00:26:49,399 --> 00:26:53,362
<i>All of the songs on that album</i>
<i>made it into the charts.</i>

681
00:26:53,445 --> 00:26:56,073
<i>You reached number two</i>
<i>on the Billboard Charts.</i>

682
00:26:56,156 --> 00:26:58,659
<i>It was awarded Best Pop Album</i>

683
00:26:58,742 --> 00:27:02,538
<i>in the 2015 Korean Music Awards.</i>

684
00:27:02,621 --> 00:27:03,872
<i>How did it feel?</i>

685
00:27:03,956 --> 00:27:06,208
If I think about it now,

686
00:27:06,291 --> 00:27:10,629
even before our debut, our songs did well.

687
00:27:10,712 --> 00:27:13,549
So even though it was surprising,

688
00:27:13,924 --> 00:27:17,094
because there hasn't been a case
when our songs weren't well-received,

689
00:27:17,553 --> 00:27:20,097
I think it was hard to actually realize

690
00:27:20,180 --> 00:27:21,682
how much of a big deal it was

691
00:27:21,765 --> 00:27:23,892
and what an honor it was.

692
00:27:24,017 --> 00:27:26,061
- Thinking about it now...
- So what you're saying is

693
00:27:26,728 --> 00:27:28,063
that it felt natural?

694
00:27:28,147 --> 00:27:30,315
- Did I understand that correctly?
- Well...

695
00:27:30,482 --> 00:27:33,110
- That's what it sounds like.
- I mean...

696
00:27:33,193 --> 00:27:34,528
- It wasn't like that.
- We understand loud and clear.

697
00:27:34,611 --> 00:27:35,988
We were like,

698
00:27:36,363 --> 00:27:37,656
"Wow, we're so grateful.

699
00:27:37,739 --> 00:27:40,033
That was really unexpected."

700
00:27:40,117 --> 00:27:44,163
But if other artists set these records,

701
00:27:44,246 --> 00:27:47,207
I think their reactions
would've been different.

702
00:27:47,291 --> 00:27:48,959
But I get why you felt that way.

703
00:27:49,042 --> 00:27:50,711
- For Chan-hyuk.
- Right.

704
00:27:51,170 --> 00:27:56,300
But looking back now after 12 years,

705
00:27:57,176 --> 00:27:58,385
I see that it was crazy.

706
00:27:58,468 --> 00:28:00,762
- Right, absolutely crazy.
- Right.

707
00:28:01,180 --> 00:28:02,598
You didn't realize that at the time.

708
00:28:02,681 --> 00:28:05,100
After that came "Last Goodbye."

709
00:28:05,434 --> 00:28:07,144
Then, "DINOSAUR."

710
00:28:08,228 --> 00:28:09,229
That's not it.

711
00:28:10,856 --> 00:28:12,316
- It's not easy.
- Right.

712
00:28:12,399 --> 00:28:13,734
It's not easy.

713
00:28:14,193 --> 00:28:15,777
- Your high notes
- Yes.

714
00:28:16,195 --> 00:28:17,905
are piercing.

715
00:28:17,988 --> 00:28:20,115
- So enchanting.
- Thank you.

716
00:28:20,199 --> 00:28:22,326
So, it was one hit after another.

717
00:28:22,701 --> 00:28:23,660
But then,

718
00:28:23,952 --> 00:28:25,537
you hit a slump.

719
00:28:26,079 --> 00:28:27,664
Chan-hyuk was doing his military service,

720
00:28:27,915 --> 00:28:31,585
and Su-hyun hit a slump
while having to go solo?

721
00:28:31,668 --> 00:28:33,754
Yes, that's right.

722
00:28:33,837 --> 00:28:37,299
Chan-hyuk does so much for me.

723
00:28:37,382 --> 00:28:38,842
But back then,

724
00:28:38,926 --> 00:28:42,512
I didn't know exactly how much that was.

725
00:28:42,596 --> 00:28:44,890
I thought it was roughly fifty-fifty.

726
00:28:44,973 --> 00:28:47,434
That was how I felt back then.

727
00:28:47,726 --> 00:28:51,813
- But it turns out, he'd been doing 90%.
- Right.

728
00:28:51,897 --> 00:28:55,442
I was clueless on how to run things
when he left to serve in the military.

729
00:28:55,609 --> 00:28:58,195
And I had to fill the hiatus by myself.

730
00:28:58,278 --> 00:29:00,280
So, confidently,

731
00:29:00,364 --> 00:29:02,366
I said I'd make my own album.

732
00:29:02,449 --> 00:29:04,284
So after declaring that, I tried to.

733
00:29:05,535 --> 00:29:06,828
But it just wasn't it.

734
00:29:07,079 --> 00:29:11,625
I realized I was arrogant.

735
00:29:11,875 --> 00:29:16,546
I had no talent for producing music.

736
00:29:16,630 --> 00:29:18,340
If I put my mind into it,

737
00:29:18,423 --> 00:29:21,718
I thought it'd be easy
to write songs like he does.

738
00:29:21,802 --> 00:29:23,011
But that wasn't the case.

739
00:29:23,095 --> 00:29:25,097
I have my talents,

740
00:29:25,430 --> 00:29:29,017
and I couldn't just do what he's good at.

741
00:29:29,101 --> 00:29:32,437
That realization put me in shock.

742
00:29:33,021 --> 00:29:35,232
So the album I made

743
00:29:35,315 --> 00:29:38,110
got buried deep inside.

744
00:29:38,193 --> 00:29:40,737
I needed some time off,

745
00:29:40,821 --> 00:29:43,573
- but the circumstances didn't allow it.
- I see.

746
00:29:43,657 --> 00:29:45,659
I lost my confidence,

747
00:29:45,742 --> 00:29:47,452
but I had to keep working.

748
00:29:47,703 --> 00:29:49,496
That's how my slump started.

749
00:29:49,579 --> 00:29:53,208
HER FIRST SLUMP WHILE HE WAS AWAY
I was just waiting for him to come back.

750
00:29:53,750 --> 00:29:56,920
And you were under the pressure
of having to make decisions.

751
00:29:57,004 --> 00:29:59,131
- That's right.
- Because of all this,

752
00:29:59,214 --> 00:30:01,508
- your self-esteem got lower.
- Yes.

753
00:30:01,591 --> 00:30:05,721
Once Chan-hyuk came back from his service,

754
00:30:05,804 --> 00:30:07,848
- you thought everything would be okay.
- Right.

755
00:30:07,931 --> 00:30:09,766
But it got worse once he came back?

756
00:30:09,850 --> 00:30:11,518
That was when it really started.

757
00:30:12,644 --> 00:30:15,022
The previous one was only the trailer.

758
00:30:15,105 --> 00:30:16,773
After he came back,

759
00:30:16,857 --> 00:30:19,109
it was like, "Wow, really?

760
00:30:19,192 --> 00:30:21,194
A person can sink this low?"

761
00:30:21,278 --> 00:30:23,238
That was the start of my real slump.

762
00:30:23,322 --> 00:30:25,407
What you experienced before
wasn't a slump?

763
00:30:25,490 --> 00:30:27,492
I would consider that just me whining.

764
00:30:29,119 --> 00:30:30,829
That's how it went.

765
00:30:30,912 --> 00:30:32,831
You have a way with words.

766
00:30:34,708 --> 00:30:36,251
Could you elaborate?

767
00:30:36,835 --> 00:30:37,919
After he came back,

768
00:30:38,003 --> 00:30:41,298
I thought I only had to focus on AKMU.

769
00:30:41,381 --> 00:30:43,175
I thought I didn't have to worry.

770
00:30:43,383 --> 00:30:44,968
I don't know what happened

771
00:30:45,052 --> 00:30:46,928
- while he was serving,
- Right.

772
00:30:47,012 --> 00:30:49,222
but he came back with a lot of ambition.

773
00:30:49,306 --> 00:30:52,517
He was burning with ambition.

774
00:30:52,601 --> 00:30:55,145
That's when <i>Sailing </i>came out.

775
00:30:55,562 --> 00:30:58,273
He was so stubborn at the time.

776
00:30:58,357 --> 00:31:00,317
Nobody could convince him.

777
00:31:00,400 --> 00:31:02,152
He was so stubborn.

778
00:31:02,235 --> 00:31:04,029
I just wanted to sing.

779
00:31:04,112 --> 00:31:06,406
But he was next to me,

780
00:31:06,490 --> 00:31:09,618
constantly arguing with our team.

781
00:31:09,701 --> 00:31:11,787
THEY WANTED DIFFERENT THINGS
That was very tiring for me.

782
00:31:12,037 --> 00:31:14,539
And then came the next album,

783
00:31:14,623 --> 00:31:17,376
called <i>NEXT EPISODE</i>.

784
00:31:17,459 --> 00:31:20,921
But that wasn't
the kind of music I wanted.

785
00:31:21,004 --> 00:31:22,714
- It wasn't.
- It wasn't to your taste.

786
00:31:22,798 --> 00:31:25,842
We were making music that I didn't like.

787
00:31:26,051 --> 00:31:29,012
It was what he was
really into at the time.

788
00:31:29,679 --> 00:31:31,765
He was pouring it out.

789
00:31:31,848 --> 00:31:34,059
It had a synth-pop song called "NAKKA."

790
00:31:35,185 --> 00:31:39,022
"NAKKA" HAD A NEW SOUND

791
00:31:39,106 --> 00:31:42,567
THAT WAS SYNTHESIZER-HEAVY

792
00:31:44,194 --> 00:31:45,278
- Princess.
- Yes?

793
00:31:45,362 --> 00:31:47,197
Was he going through puberty again?

794
00:31:48,115 --> 00:31:50,409
- No, it was a long time coming.
- Yes.

795
00:31:50,492 --> 00:31:52,035
It was bound to happen.

796
00:31:52,702 --> 00:31:55,789
Something dark inside of him...

797
00:31:56,164 --> 00:31:57,332
It wasn't dark.

798
00:31:57,416 --> 00:31:58,917
- It wasn't?
- It was red. Passion.

799
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:00,210
- Okay, red.
- Yes.

800
00:32:00,293 --> 00:32:01,336
It wasn't dark.

801
00:32:01,420 --> 00:32:04,714
Something red inside of him
turned way too red-hot.

802
00:32:05,674 --> 00:32:08,176
He couldn't be stopped.

803
00:32:08,260 --> 00:32:10,095
I really didn't want to do it,

804
00:32:10,178 --> 00:32:11,596
but I couldn't stop him.

805
00:32:11,930 --> 00:32:13,014
He was like...

806
00:32:14,182 --> 00:32:15,809
He was letting it all out.

807
00:32:15,892 --> 00:32:17,602
So I had to hold it in.

808
00:32:17,686 --> 00:32:19,062
In that period,

809
00:32:19,146 --> 00:32:23,400
I told him that this was my limit.

810
00:32:23,525 --> 00:32:24,943
I told him that

811
00:32:25,026 --> 00:32:28,738
I could no longer follow
the music he pursued.

812
00:32:28,822 --> 00:32:31,741
I said I'd have to quit AKMU.

813
00:32:31,825 --> 00:32:32,993
I have to ask.

814
00:32:33,076 --> 00:32:35,912
- Yes?
- Why did you want to change AKMU's sound?

815
00:32:35,996 --> 00:32:39,541
Did you know Su-hyun
felt this way at the time?

816
00:32:39,624 --> 00:32:40,834
Not entirely.

817
00:32:40,917 --> 00:32:44,671
I didn't expect the change
that Su-hyun went through after that

818
00:32:44,921 --> 00:32:46,131
at the time.

819
00:32:46,214 --> 00:32:47,632
I thought it was just a slump.

820
00:32:48,592 --> 00:32:51,386
As for me, in order for AKMU
to make it in the long run,

821
00:32:51,470 --> 00:32:54,306
I thought we had to
take a different direction.

822
00:32:54,639 --> 00:32:57,267
"Are we always going to be
the nice siblings?

823
00:32:57,559 --> 00:33:00,854
How long are we going to stay
the cute, bubbly kids?"

824
00:33:00,937 --> 00:33:02,606
We're going to get old.

825
00:33:02,898 --> 00:33:05,192
I thought we had to level up,

826
00:33:05,358 --> 00:33:07,611
along with the quality
of our performances.

827
00:33:07,694 --> 00:33:09,988
That's what that album was about.

828
00:33:10,071 --> 00:33:11,823
Just as growing can be painful,

829
00:33:11,907 --> 00:33:14,367
you thought it was time
for you to grow up.

830
00:33:14,659 --> 00:33:18,580
Ironically, the message that "NAKKA" holds

831
00:33:18,788 --> 00:33:22,626
was something
that I wanted Su-hyun to hear.

832
00:33:22,709 --> 00:33:25,420
"Even if you crashed

833
00:33:25,837 --> 00:33:28,340
deep down into a pit,

834
00:33:28,423 --> 00:33:31,092
I'd hold your hand and jump with you.

835
00:33:31,301 --> 00:33:34,763
Because I don't just love you
when you're up high.

836
00:33:35,222 --> 00:33:36,848
Even when you're at your lowest,

837
00:33:36,932 --> 00:33:39,267
I love you enough to jump down

838
00:33:39,351 --> 00:33:40,602
together with you."

839
00:33:40,685 --> 00:33:43,939
I thought that would comfort Su-hyun,

840
00:33:44,606 --> 00:33:48,610
but she was already at the point

841
00:33:48,860 --> 00:33:52,864
where nothing could get through to her.

842
00:33:52,948 --> 00:33:53,949
That's right.

843
00:33:54,616 --> 00:33:59,496
I TOLD YOU THAT WHEN THE DAY CAME,
I WOULDN'T LEAVE YOU ALONE

844
00:33:59,579 --> 00:34:03,583
WE'RE SURROUNDED BY CLIFFS, LOOK
IT MIGHT HURT EVEN MORE THAN WE THOUGHT

845
00:34:03,667 --> 00:34:07,546
BUT CLOSE YOUR EYES AND FALL
TRUST ME, CLOSE YOUR EYES AND FALL

846
00:34:07,629 --> 00:34:09,130
NOTHING CAN BREAK US

847
00:34:09,214 --> 00:34:10,966
FROM "NAKKA"

848
00:34:11,049 --> 00:34:13,260
- You just mentioned irony.
- Yes.

849
00:34:13,343 --> 00:34:14,594
- What's also ironic
- Yes?

850
00:34:14,678 --> 00:34:17,097
is that a great song
was born in that period.

851
00:34:17,847 --> 00:34:21,393
AKMU's biggest hit song that put
even Han Kang, the writer, in tears.

852
00:34:21,476 --> 00:34:25,939
"How Can I Love the Heartbreak,
You're the One I Love."

853
00:34:26,606 --> 00:34:29,192
Did you go through a difficult breakup?
Was it based on experience?

854
00:34:29,276 --> 00:34:31,069
Was it really bad?

855
00:34:31,152 --> 00:34:32,737
How did you write this song?

856
00:34:32,904 --> 00:34:35,699
I think the breakup was ordinary,

857
00:34:35,782 --> 00:34:37,826
but there was another level

858
00:34:37,909 --> 00:34:41,246
of contemplation about the breakup.

859
00:34:41,955 --> 00:34:43,873
Did you watch Han Kang's interview?

860
00:34:44,207 --> 00:34:45,250
- Yes.
- Yes, I did.

861
00:34:45,875 --> 00:34:47,794
I wondered how you would've felt

862
00:34:49,004 --> 00:34:52,048
hearing that your song
brought tears to Han Kang's eyes.

863
00:34:52,132 --> 00:34:53,883
That's just...

864
00:34:55,135 --> 00:34:56,886
I can't imagine how it would feel.

865
00:34:56,970 --> 00:34:58,430
Could you tell me?

866
00:34:58,763 --> 00:35:00,390
- Han Kang was moved.
- I don't feel any differently.

867
00:35:00,473 --> 00:35:02,183
To be completely honest,

868
00:35:03,435 --> 00:35:05,020
Han Kang saying

869
00:35:05,228 --> 00:35:08,106
that she loved our song

870
00:35:08,857 --> 00:35:10,609
and a fan of ours saying

871
00:35:10,734 --> 00:35:12,152
that it's their favorite

872
00:35:12,235 --> 00:35:15,572
hold the same weight for me.

873
00:35:15,655 --> 00:35:16,656
So,

874
00:35:17,073 --> 00:35:18,825
I'm grateful just the same.

875
00:35:22,370 --> 00:35:23,580
He really is something else.

876
00:35:24,456 --> 00:35:26,625
I, on the other hand, am very grateful.

877
00:35:27,917 --> 00:35:30,754
As for me, I'd like to say
that I'm super grateful.

878
00:35:30,837 --> 00:35:32,797
Of course, I'm grateful too.

879
00:35:33,131 --> 00:35:35,508
HIS ANSWER WAS NICE, THOUGH
She's a famous writer.

880
00:35:35,634 --> 00:35:39,638
It's not easy for a writer
to win the Nobel Prize in Literature,

881
00:35:39,721 --> 00:35:41,723
- but she did what we thought impossible.
- She did.

882
00:35:41,806 --> 00:35:44,267
- Goodness.
- And she mentioned us.

883
00:35:44,351 --> 00:35:46,978
Thanks to that,
we made it back into the charts.

884
00:35:47,062 --> 00:35:48,438
- Is that so?
- Yes.

885
00:35:48,521 --> 00:35:51,983
So I'm grateful in that sense, too.

886
00:35:52,108 --> 00:35:56,863
I'm deeply moved and very honored.

887
00:35:57,572 --> 00:35:58,740
That scratched my itch.

888
00:36:02,869 --> 00:36:05,914
Let's move on to your solo projects.

889
00:36:07,832 --> 00:36:09,709
You shaved your head on stage, on TV?

890
00:36:10,460 --> 00:36:11,378
Yes.

891
00:36:12,545 --> 00:36:16,299
CHAN-HYUK WENT VIRAL
FOR HIS SOLO PROJECT PERFORMANCES

892
00:36:18,301 --> 00:36:19,386
SHAVED HIS HEAD ON TV

893
00:36:19,469 --> 00:36:21,179
A SHOCKING PERFORMANCE,
"I CAN'T DIE LIKE THIS"

894
00:36:21,262 --> 00:36:22,889
CONVEYING A STRONG MESSAGE
OR BEING EXCESSIVE?

895
00:36:25,183 --> 00:36:28,186
HE EVEN HAD A FUNERAL ON STAGE

896
00:36:28,645 --> 00:36:30,105
When I was making my album,

897
00:36:30,188 --> 00:36:32,315
I got to think again

898
00:36:32,565 --> 00:36:36,486
about the things
I thought I wasn't interested in

899
00:36:36,569 --> 00:36:37,904
up to that point.

900
00:36:38,154 --> 00:36:40,615
At the time, I'd always say,

901
00:36:41,074 --> 00:36:43,952
"I don't care if I die today or tomorrow.

902
00:36:44,035 --> 00:36:47,747
Because I'm satisfied

903
00:36:48,039 --> 00:36:50,500
- with the life I'm living every day."
- I see.

904
00:36:51,209 --> 00:36:54,421
But when I was making the album,

905
00:36:54,671 --> 00:36:56,756
I really wanted the album to come out.

906
00:36:56,840 --> 00:36:59,092
HIS FIRST SOLO ALBUM, <i>ERROR</i>
I wanted to do all these performances.

907
00:36:59,175 --> 00:37:01,553
I said I was okay with dying,

908
00:37:01,678 --> 00:37:04,431
but I didn't want to die
before the album came out.

909
00:37:04,514 --> 00:37:06,099
So my mindset changed.

910
00:37:06,558 --> 00:37:08,935
That's why my song says,

911
00:37:09,227 --> 00:37:10,478
"I can't die like this.

912
00:37:10,562 --> 00:37:12,105
I have to do everything
on my bucket list."

913
00:37:12,439 --> 00:37:14,274
So, what was on my bucket list?

914
00:37:14,774 --> 00:37:16,317
I listed those things,

915
00:37:16,401 --> 00:37:19,112
and did them as performances.

916
00:37:20,655 --> 00:37:22,949
The problem is,
the fans may be fine with it

917
00:37:23,032 --> 00:37:25,034
- but it's different for your parents.
- Right.

918
00:37:25,660 --> 00:37:27,537
When your parents saw that,

919
00:37:27,787 --> 00:37:30,123
they must've been concerned.

920
00:37:30,206 --> 00:37:31,416
Weren't they?

921
00:37:33,418 --> 00:37:34,753
By that point,

922
00:37:35,503 --> 00:37:37,130
I was already beyond the area of concern.

923
00:37:37,213 --> 00:37:38,173
HE WAS TOO FAR GONE

924
00:37:38,381 --> 00:37:40,675
Our parents were
just praying at that point.

925
00:37:42,343 --> 00:37:44,596
They don't even try to talk to him now.

926
00:37:44,679 --> 00:37:46,973
All they do is pray.

927
00:37:47,515 --> 00:37:49,309
They pray to the Lord.

928
00:37:49,392 --> 00:37:50,518
BEYOND HUMAN CONTROL

929
00:37:50,602 --> 00:37:52,312
"Please protect our son."

930
00:37:52,812 --> 00:37:54,731
But Lee Chan-hyuk does it again.

931
00:37:55,315 --> 00:37:57,317
Your second solo album from 2025,

932
00:37:57,400 --> 00:37:59,569
<i>EROS</i> was awarded
by the Korean Music Awards

933
00:37:59,652 --> 00:38:01,029
Best Pop Album,

934
00:38:01,112 --> 00:38:04,449
Best Pop Song, and Song of the Year.

935
00:38:04,532 --> 00:38:06,785
You won three awards.

936
00:38:07,076 --> 00:38:08,244
How did you feel?

937
00:38:08,328 --> 00:38:09,245
TRIPLE CROWN

938
00:38:10,622 --> 00:38:11,956
I was very happy.

939
00:38:12,290 --> 00:38:14,083
- And--
- Those awards are the same

940
00:38:14,167 --> 00:38:15,710
as all the other awards, right?

941
00:38:16,085 --> 00:38:19,047
GOOD AT MEMORIZING THINGS TO MAKE FUN OF
Every award is equal.

942
00:38:20,298 --> 00:38:21,341
The point is

943
00:38:21,841 --> 00:38:24,344
that even if I didn't win those awards,

944
00:38:24,636 --> 00:38:28,807
I would've felt the same way
about this album.

945
00:38:28,890 --> 00:38:32,143
There's a sincere message in the album,

946
00:38:32,352 --> 00:38:34,145
and it's my best work.

947
00:38:35,188 --> 00:38:38,691
But he couldn't make it
to the awards show.

948
00:38:38,775 --> 00:38:42,570
As soon as it was over,
he told the manager,

949
00:38:43,363 --> 00:38:44,656
"Bring me my awards."

950
00:38:45,907 --> 00:38:46,741
"Where are my awards?"

951
00:38:46,825 --> 00:38:48,743
- "Bring them at once."
- "All three."

952
00:38:49,577 --> 00:38:51,871
"Bring all three.
I have to take a picture."

953
00:38:51,955 --> 00:38:53,748
"Every award is the same, but..."

954
00:38:53,832 --> 00:38:55,208
- "Yes, but..."
- "Bring them."

955
00:38:55,291 --> 00:38:56,501
We don't know why,

956
00:38:56,584 --> 00:39:00,505
but he wanted his three KMA trophies.

957
00:39:00,964 --> 00:39:02,382
I was very grateful.

958
00:39:03,341 --> 00:39:05,176
The truth is, he was grateful.

959
00:39:08,346 --> 00:39:11,641
Let's travel back in time
so you can give your speech.

960
00:39:12,225 --> 00:39:13,268
The triple crown.

961
00:39:13,351 --> 00:39:14,477
HIS EXCLUSIVE SPEECH

962
00:39:14,561 --> 00:39:15,937
Lee Chan-hyuk!

963
00:39:16,020 --> 00:39:17,105
Oh, now?

964
00:39:17,981 --> 00:39:18,982
Just like that?

965
00:39:19,649 --> 00:39:20,525
Out of nowhere.

966
00:39:20,608 --> 00:39:22,277
- Thank you.
- For the first time!

967
00:39:22,527 --> 00:39:24,320
All right. Let me give you the mic.

968
00:39:25,572 --> 00:39:26,406
KOREAN MUSIC AWARDS
LEE CHAN-HYUK

969
00:39:26,489 --> 00:39:28,283
I have to say,

970
00:39:28,908 --> 00:39:31,035
five years ago,

971
00:39:31,202 --> 00:39:35,790
I would never have imagined
that I'd be the person that I am now.

972
00:39:35,874 --> 00:39:38,209
You never really know
what will happen in life.

973
00:39:38,293 --> 00:39:42,964
If you focus on things you want to do
and things that you love,

974
00:39:43,256 --> 00:39:45,675
try your best,
and give it all your energy,

975
00:39:46,843 --> 00:39:49,178
you'll see that you've become someone

976
00:39:49,262 --> 00:39:52,348
even you wouldn't have expected.

977
00:39:52,432 --> 00:39:53,725
I'm so grateful

978
00:39:53,933 --> 00:39:55,643
for all the love I've received.

979
00:39:56,269 --> 00:40:00,315
I hope your days are
filled with passion and love.

980
00:40:02,108 --> 00:40:04,611
Once again, congratulations.

981
00:40:05,778 --> 00:40:07,614
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

982
00:40:07,697 --> 00:40:10,700
"Love Lee" is a song with special meaning.

983
00:40:10,783 --> 00:40:11,701
What is that?

984
00:40:11,826 --> 00:40:13,703
For my solo project,

985
00:40:14,245 --> 00:40:16,748
I did everything on my bucket list.

986
00:40:16,956 --> 00:40:18,207
When I was done,

987
00:40:18,917 --> 00:40:21,252
Su-hyun was just there by herself.

988
00:40:22,003 --> 00:40:23,504
She was literally just there

989
00:40:23,880 --> 00:40:25,214
without doing anything

990
00:40:25,715 --> 00:40:26,716
but playing games.

991
00:40:27,550 --> 00:40:28,968
- That's something.
- Yes.

992
00:40:29,052 --> 00:40:30,136
That's right.

993
00:40:30,553 --> 00:40:32,055
- Like "Fry's Dream."
- Yes.

994
00:40:32,430 --> 00:40:33,598
But if the egg was bad.

995
00:40:35,391 --> 00:40:36,601
- Was it bad?
- Yes.

996
00:40:36,684 --> 00:40:38,102
It turned black.

997
00:40:38,186 --> 00:40:40,063
The yolk is supposed to be yellow,

998
00:40:40,897 --> 00:40:41,940
but it was black.

999
00:40:42,649 --> 00:40:43,733
- That's true.
- Yes.

1000
00:40:43,942 --> 00:40:45,360
But she was saying

1001
00:40:45,652 --> 00:40:47,779
that she was okay

1002
00:40:48,071 --> 00:40:49,739
- Right. It was ridiculous.
- and happy.

1003
00:40:49,948 --> 00:40:50,990
She thought so.

1004
00:40:51,074 --> 00:40:53,159
But everyone around her knew

1005
00:40:53,534 --> 00:40:54,619
that Su-hyun

1006
00:40:54,953 --> 00:40:56,329
had hit a serious slump.

1007
00:40:56,788 --> 00:40:58,289
THE CONSECUTIVE SLUMPS TOOK A TOLL ON HER

1008
00:40:58,373 --> 00:40:59,916
I went over to her place.

1009
00:41:00,416 --> 00:41:04,420
We actually don't have
a lot of serious conversations.

1010
00:41:04,504 --> 00:41:06,547
We barely have one in a year.

1011
00:41:06,631 --> 00:41:09,175
But that day,

1012
00:41:09,258 --> 00:41:13,054
we had the most serious conversation
in AKMU's history

1013
00:41:13,221 --> 00:41:15,139
about our future.

1014
00:41:15,223 --> 00:41:16,724
I offered heartfelt words.

1015
00:41:17,392 --> 00:41:21,729
I told her I wanted AKMU to make a song
that she'd have fun with.

1016
00:41:21,813 --> 00:41:24,649
While making songs, at some point,

1017
00:41:24,857 --> 00:41:28,194
I stopped respecting her opinion.

1018
00:41:28,277 --> 00:41:31,155
I forced things on her,

1019
00:41:31,614 --> 00:41:33,533
and that had an effect on her slump.

1020
00:41:33,741 --> 00:41:37,203
I wanted us to do songs
like the ones from our first album

1021
00:41:37,578 --> 00:41:40,164
that she had so much fun with.

1022
00:41:40,581 --> 00:41:43,251
I suggested we do a song called "Love Lee"

1023
00:41:43,334 --> 00:41:45,294
that I'd already written.

1024
00:41:45,712 --> 00:41:46,546
Yes.

1025
00:41:46,629 --> 00:41:48,381
How did you feel, Su-hyun?

1026
00:41:48,673 --> 00:41:50,008
At the time,

1027
00:41:50,800 --> 00:41:54,887
I had absolutely no energy for anything.

1028
00:41:55,304 --> 00:41:58,433
I had given up on a lot of things.

1029
00:41:58,516 --> 00:42:01,310
Being back on TV

1030
00:42:01,394 --> 00:42:05,481
and having fun
while singing in front of the camera

1031
00:42:05,982 --> 00:42:09,569
were things I thought
I'd never do again at the time.

1032
00:42:10,028 --> 00:42:13,656
The deal that Chan-hyuk gave me

1033
00:42:13,906 --> 00:42:17,326
was that he'd make a song
that I'd have fun with.

1034
00:42:17,744 --> 00:42:21,205
I'd given up on a lot of things,

1035
00:42:21,289 --> 00:42:23,958
but I was still holding on to one thing.

1036
00:42:24,292 --> 00:42:25,668
I wanted to sing.

1037
00:42:25,752 --> 00:42:28,463
"If I start having fun singing again,

1038
00:42:28,546 --> 00:42:31,674
maybe I'll enjoy working again."

1039
00:42:31,758 --> 00:42:34,010
Those were the expectations
I had going in.

1040
00:42:34,093 --> 00:42:36,387
But what had me scared the most

1041
00:42:36,471 --> 00:42:41,309
was that I remembered
what it felt like to be loved.

1042
00:42:41,601 --> 00:42:43,728
I knew the feeling very well.

1043
00:42:43,811 --> 00:42:48,107
And I also knew the reasons
why people loved me very well.

1044
00:42:48,191 --> 00:42:49,984
But when I looked at myself,

1045
00:42:50,068 --> 00:42:51,819
I was no longer that person.

1046
00:42:52,070 --> 00:42:53,988
I was not the person

1047
00:42:54,072 --> 00:42:56,407
that people were expecting me to be.

1048
00:42:56,491 --> 00:42:57,992
I was a different person.

1049
00:42:58,826 --> 00:43:00,745
"Are people still going to like me

1050
00:43:01,079 --> 00:43:04,123
just because I'm singing a nice song?"

1051
00:43:04,207 --> 00:43:07,668
That was my biggest fear.

1052
00:43:08,002 --> 00:43:09,087
That's why

1053
00:43:09,712 --> 00:43:12,465
it was a big challenge for me.

1054
00:43:12,548 --> 00:43:14,175
If I experienced

1055
00:43:14,592 --> 00:43:17,303
being ignored by people,

1056
00:43:17,678 --> 00:43:19,430
I thought that'd break me.

1057
00:43:19,514 --> 00:43:21,307
I had that in mind.

1058
00:43:21,390 --> 00:43:24,310
But Chan-hyuk kept encouraging me.

1059
00:43:24,393 --> 00:43:25,520
He gave me courage.

1060
00:43:25,728 --> 00:43:26,854
"Let's give it a try."

1061
00:43:26,938 --> 00:43:28,773
I took small steps of courage

1062
00:43:29,482 --> 00:43:32,610
and we performed "Love Lee."

1063
00:43:33,319 --> 00:43:34,362
I think

1064
00:43:34,821 --> 00:43:38,783
that period with that song saved me.

1065
00:43:39,367 --> 00:43:41,953
Because my perception

1066
00:43:42,036 --> 00:43:44,163
<i>of why people liked me</i>

1067
00:43:44,247 --> 00:43:47,250
<i>was completely shattered.</i>

1068
00:43:47,333 --> 00:43:50,586
<i>There were so many people who liked me</i>

1069
00:43:50,670 --> 00:43:52,088
<i>just for who I was.</i>

1070
00:43:52,171 --> 00:43:55,383
There were so many people
who just wanted me to be happy.

1071
00:43:55,466 --> 00:43:59,887
It would already be an amazing thing
to have one person

1072
00:44:00,263 --> 00:44:02,515
- who loves me that much.
- Right.

1073
00:44:02,682 --> 00:44:04,183
But I had so many.

1074
00:44:04,267 --> 00:44:08,980
It felt like I was a one-in-a-million
person of importance.

1075
00:44:09,063 --> 00:44:13,359
<i>I wanted to be strong</i>
<i>and repay the people who loved me.</i>

1076
00:44:13,442 --> 00:44:17,321
I got my motivation back.

1077
00:44:19,740 --> 00:44:22,451
I, Hocrates, think,

1078
00:44:22,660 --> 00:44:24,370
- even though I don't know much,
- Yes?

1079
00:44:24,787 --> 00:44:28,541
that your voice is a treasure
and a source of comfort.

1080
00:44:29,834 --> 00:44:30,960
Thank you.

1081
00:44:32,753 --> 00:44:34,422
SOARING FREELY, FLUTTER FLUTTER

1082
00:44:34,505 --> 00:44:36,883
I JUMPED IN KNOWING
FLOWERS WOULD SWALLOW ME

1083
00:44:36,966 --> 00:44:39,218
I'LL GIVE YOU EVERYTHING
AND BECOME PENNILESS

1084
00:44:39,302 --> 00:44:41,429
JUBILATE, APPLAUSE
WHO WOULDN'T FALL IN LOVE?

1085
00:44:41,512 --> 00:44:42,346
FROM "LOVE LEE"

1086
00:44:42,430 --> 00:44:46,058
Your company's name
is Cemter of Inspiration.

1087
00:44:46,225 --> 00:44:48,269
- You once held a solo exhibition.
- Yes.

1088
00:44:48,352 --> 00:44:49,687
What was that called?

1089
00:44:49,770 --> 00:44:51,606
- Cemter of Inspiration.
- Right.

1090
00:44:51,689 --> 00:44:53,441
CEMTER OF INSPIRATION: LAST DROP

1091
00:44:53,524 --> 00:44:55,651
IMMERSIVE EXHIBITION
DESIGNED TO LET PEOPLE

1092
00:44:55,735 --> 00:44:57,653
EXPERIENCE CHAN-HYUK'S
MUSICAL INSPIRATIONS

1093
00:44:57,737 --> 00:44:59,071
Could you read this?

1094
00:44:59,614 --> 00:45:02,950
"Put this on your skin.
This is my sweat and our accomplishment.

1095
00:45:03,034 --> 00:45:05,369
TEXT AT THE EXHIBITION
The old is gone, and all is made new."

1096
00:45:05,453 --> 00:45:06,621
It's like something from the Bible.

1097
00:45:07,205 --> 00:45:08,915
Put what on your skin?

1098
00:45:08,998 --> 00:45:11,459
- "Spring water" was provided there.
- Okay.

1099
00:45:11,542 --> 00:45:13,085
And it was actually

1100
00:45:13,377 --> 00:45:15,338
my sweat.

1101
00:45:16,088 --> 00:45:17,423
He put his sweat in it...

1102
00:45:18,799 --> 00:45:19,759
DOING HIS BEST TO UNDERSTAND

1103
00:45:19,842 --> 00:45:22,345
...and let people rub it on their skin.

1104
00:45:23,471 --> 00:45:25,723
It's useless... I mean, useful.

1105
00:45:26,098 --> 00:45:27,391
- You said it's useless.
- It's useful.

1106
00:45:27,475 --> 00:45:30,937
SPRING WATER MADE OF
CHAN-HYUK'S INSPIRATION, AKA SWEAT

1107
00:45:31,020 --> 00:45:34,732
PEOPLE EACH GOT JUST ONE DROP

1108
00:45:34,815 --> 00:45:36,901
Could you explain this piece?

1109
00:45:36,984 --> 00:45:38,319
In the exhibition space,

1110
00:45:38,402 --> 00:45:43,282
I wrung every last drop
of my sweat out of those

1111
00:45:43,366 --> 00:45:44,492
and hung them there.

1112
00:45:46,702 --> 00:45:47,995
What is he saying?

1113
00:45:48,079 --> 00:45:49,163
I'm not sure, either.

1114
00:45:49,247 --> 00:45:50,331
SATISFIED
Through the wringer?

1115
00:45:50,414 --> 00:45:51,249
Yes.

1116
00:45:51,624 --> 00:45:53,751
- Here it is. Cemter of Inspiration.
- Yes.

1117
00:45:53,834 --> 00:45:55,461
- Yes.
- This is where

1118
00:45:55,878 --> 00:45:58,339
people rubbed my sweat on their skin.

1119
00:45:58,422 --> 00:46:00,258
They had to kneel as it happened.

1120
00:46:00,883 --> 00:46:02,885
- "I took off my shoes, knelt politely,
- Yes.

1121
00:46:02,969 --> 00:46:05,096
and received the spring water on my hand."

1122
00:46:05,805 --> 00:46:07,932
I didn't put this on my skin,

1123
00:46:08,015 --> 00:46:10,851
but according to the people who did,

1124
00:46:11,102 --> 00:46:12,436
the smell was sour

1125
00:46:12,520 --> 00:46:14,689
and it lasted long.

1126
00:46:15,690 --> 00:46:17,566
Yes, that's right.

1127
00:46:18,234 --> 00:46:20,653
This person must have wanted
to know really badly.

1128
00:46:20,736 --> 00:46:22,655
"I asked if it was really his sweat.

1129
00:46:22,738 --> 00:46:24,615
I was surprised to hear that it was."

1130
00:46:25,574 --> 00:46:26,534
Thank you.

1131
00:46:27,118 --> 00:46:28,327
It's not something that's that surprising.

1132
00:46:29,036 --> 00:46:31,414
So, why did you make that
the company name?

1133
00:46:32,957 --> 00:46:35,751
The Cemter of Inspiration exhibition

1134
00:46:35,835 --> 00:46:37,878
was another level of campy.

1135
00:46:37,962 --> 00:46:39,005
It was beyond campy.

1136
00:46:39,088 --> 00:46:41,841
And as we started this company,

1137
00:46:41,924 --> 00:46:44,593
we posted a teaser video.

1138
00:46:44,677 --> 00:46:47,013
That had a similar vibe.

1139
00:46:47,471 --> 00:46:52,184
THE FIRST TEASER THAT AKMU POSTED
ABOUT THEIR NEW COMPANY

1140
00:47:07,491 --> 00:47:09,243
And there's also that.

1141
00:47:09,327 --> 00:47:12,872
Ever since we were kids,
we were asked about our inspiration

1142
00:47:12,955 --> 00:47:14,332
so many times.

1143
00:47:15,124 --> 00:47:17,126
"Where do you get your inspiration?"

1144
00:47:17,251 --> 00:47:20,087
I thought I already gave an answer
after our first album.

1145
00:47:20,379 --> 00:47:21,714
But even now,

1146
00:47:22,006 --> 00:47:24,884
they never skip this question.

1147
00:47:24,967 --> 00:47:27,636
I always have to answer this question.

1148
00:47:27,928 --> 00:47:29,263
So I thought of something.

1149
00:47:30,181 --> 00:47:32,558
Let's just tell them
our inspiration is at home.

1150
00:47:33,184 --> 00:47:35,144
"We have a center of inspiration,
like a fountain,

1151
00:47:35,227 --> 00:47:37,104
at home and where we work,

1152
00:47:37,188 --> 00:47:39,190
so we drink a spoonful every day."

1153
00:47:39,273 --> 00:47:42,109
Kind of like
Willy Wonka's chocolate factory.

1154
00:47:42,193 --> 00:47:44,153
Not <i>"yeonggam"</i> as in "old man"?

1155
00:47:44,236 --> 00:47:49,825
That's actually what we call
people who work at our company.

1156
00:47:50,117 --> 00:47:53,287
Like Yeonggam Hwang, Yeonggam No,

1157
00:47:53,371 --> 00:47:55,247
- Yeonggam Kim.
- Yeonggam Kim.

1158
00:47:55,331 --> 00:47:57,500
That's what we call them.

1159
00:47:57,583 --> 00:48:01,128
So, is the new album coming soon?
When is it coming?

1160
00:48:02,088 --> 00:48:03,297
On April 7.

1161
00:48:03,381 --> 00:48:05,007
On the anniversary of our debut.

1162
00:48:05,383 --> 00:48:06,717
Like we're being reborn.

1163
00:48:06,801 --> 00:48:08,219
I see.

1164
00:48:08,594 --> 00:48:09,637
- Since it's spring.
- Yes.

1165
00:48:09,720 --> 00:48:11,514
The album is called <i>FLOWERING</i>.

1166
00:48:11,806 --> 00:48:14,475
We thought about our flowering season

1167
00:48:14,558 --> 00:48:15,935
and realized it's now.

1168
00:48:16,018 --> 00:48:18,187
Age-wise and experience-wise,

1169
00:48:18,729 --> 00:48:19,939
this is our best moment.

1170
00:48:20,231 --> 00:48:21,399
We're flowering.

1171
00:48:22,149 --> 00:48:24,735
So <i>FLOWERING</i> is coming April 7.

1172
00:48:25,444 --> 00:48:26,987
You'll be in full bloom soon.

1173
00:48:27,113 --> 00:48:28,114
That's right.

1174
00:48:28,948 --> 00:48:30,741
You did volunteer work in Africa?

1175
00:48:30,825 --> 00:48:31,909
Yes.

1176
00:48:32,410 --> 00:48:35,413
But calling it volunteer work...

1177
00:48:35,496 --> 00:48:37,832
I don't want to call it that.

1178
00:48:37,915 --> 00:48:40,918
- It sounds one-sided.
- I see.

1179
00:48:41,419 --> 00:48:42,837
But it was reciprocal.

1180
00:48:42,920 --> 00:48:45,881
<i>We gave love and also received it.</i>

1181
00:48:45,965 --> 00:48:47,591
<i>That was the experience.</i>

1182
00:48:47,883 --> 00:48:50,010
<i>We went together with our Yeonggams.</i>

1183
00:48:50,094 --> 00:48:51,637
They all came with.

1184
00:48:51,720 --> 00:48:52,721
All together.

1185
00:48:53,013 --> 00:48:55,724
Anything we do, we all do it together.

1186
00:48:55,808 --> 00:48:58,018
<i>We feel things together, give feedback,</i>

1187
00:48:58,102 --> 00:48:59,520
<i>and grow together.</i>

1188
00:48:59,603 --> 00:49:02,231
<i>That shapes the soul of the company.</i>

1189
00:49:02,898 --> 00:49:05,818
All of us felt that experience together.

1190
00:49:05,943 --> 00:49:08,988
We wanted to take this positive energy,

1191
00:49:09,071 --> 00:49:11,490
put it in this album,

1192
00:49:11,574 --> 00:49:13,409
and spread it to people.

1193
00:49:13,492 --> 00:49:15,202
You wanted to pack it tightly.

1194
00:49:15,286 --> 00:49:17,121
- That's right.
- All of it.

1195
00:49:17,204 --> 00:49:18,456
- Pack it all in there.
- Yes.

1196
00:49:18,914 --> 00:49:20,082
What's the title track?

1197
00:49:20,207 --> 00:49:23,377
It's called
"Joy, Sorrow, A Beautiful Heart."

1198
00:49:24,253 --> 00:49:26,172
I think when we're young,

1199
00:49:26,797 --> 00:49:29,133
we think of the joy after sorrow

1200
00:49:29,216 --> 00:49:30,926
as a good thing

1201
00:49:31,010 --> 00:49:32,136
with no doubt.

1202
00:49:32,219 --> 00:49:35,097
But we think of the sorrow after joy

1203
00:49:35,181 --> 00:49:38,017
as relatively disappointing.

1204
00:49:38,225 --> 00:49:40,978
However, from my experience,

1205
00:49:41,145 --> 00:49:44,565
the sorrow that comes after joy

1206
00:49:44,815 --> 00:49:46,609
is part of the deal.

1207
00:49:46,859 --> 00:49:48,360
When we feel sorrow,

1208
00:49:48,444 --> 00:49:50,696
if we think about where it comes from,

1209
00:49:50,779 --> 00:49:52,740
it makes us think deeper

1210
00:49:52,823 --> 00:49:55,826
about how valuable the joy is.

1211
00:49:56,243 --> 00:49:58,078
To make it easier to understand,

1212
00:49:58,162 --> 00:50:01,290
let's say I had someone and they left.

1213
00:50:01,457 --> 00:50:04,668
If I feel sorrow because they left,

1214
00:50:04,835 --> 00:50:07,713
that means they gave me joy.

1215
00:50:08,672 --> 00:50:11,217
It's part of what makes
the heart and feelings beautiful.

1216
00:50:11,842 --> 00:50:14,220
Could we hear a part of it?

1217
00:50:14,803 --> 00:50:17,765
- It starts like this.
- Let's hear our princess's voice.

1218
00:50:17,848 --> 00:50:19,475
Attention, everyone.

1219
00:50:20,893 --> 00:50:22,603
I haven't sung this anywhere yet.

1220
00:50:22,686 --> 00:50:23,938
I'm suddenly really nervous.

1221
00:50:28,359 --> 00:50:34,198
<i>When sorrow comes after joy</i>

1222
00:50:34,865 --> 00:50:38,494
<i>It's what makes a beautiful heart</i>

1223
00:50:40,538 --> 00:50:46,126
<i>Don't chase it away, embrace it</i>

1224
00:50:46,919 --> 00:50:51,006
<i>It will become a very pretty stone</i>

1225
00:50:52,049 --> 00:50:53,592
That's how the song starts.

1226
00:50:56,303 --> 00:50:57,346
Must be nice, right?

1227
00:50:57,429 --> 00:50:58,389
I'm so jealous.

1228
00:50:59,974 --> 00:51:01,267
Thank you.

1229
00:51:01,350 --> 00:51:02,601
What are your thoughts on it?

1230
00:51:03,102 --> 00:51:05,229
"That's my sister!" That's how I feel.

1231
00:51:05,896 --> 00:51:07,398
I like that.

1232
00:51:07,481 --> 00:51:09,733
"Yes! That's my sister."

1233
00:51:11,402 --> 00:51:14,780
The best all-around artists
of the 21st century, AKMU.

1234
00:51:15,072 --> 00:51:16,490
What future do you dream of?

1235
00:51:16,574 --> 00:51:17,950
THE FUTURE AKMU DREAMS OF

1236
00:51:18,325 --> 00:51:19,952
This is what I've been thinking for
a few years.

1237
00:51:20,160 --> 00:51:22,830
It's really hard to do something
for a very long time.

1238
00:51:23,539 --> 00:51:26,166
I realized and started to see you

1239
00:51:26,417 --> 00:51:28,502
and everyone else
who has done something for years.

1240
00:51:28,586 --> 00:51:30,170
Now I have much more respect

1241
00:51:30,254 --> 00:51:31,880
for that consistency.

1242
00:51:32,172 --> 00:51:33,882
I want us to be a group like that.

1243
00:51:34,216 --> 00:51:36,969
I want us to grow old with the people

1244
00:51:37,052 --> 00:51:38,846
who listen to our music.

1245
00:51:38,929 --> 00:51:40,431
- I see.
- That's AKMU's dream.

1246
00:51:41,890 --> 00:51:42,975
It's not easy, right?

1247
00:51:43,058 --> 00:51:44,643
Right, it's really difficult.

1248
00:51:44,893 --> 00:51:46,520
It's hard to do something for a long time.

1249
00:51:46,895 --> 00:51:48,647
I feel the same way.

1250
00:51:48,731 --> 00:51:51,025
That's why I'm focused on

1251
00:51:51,442 --> 00:51:53,861
staying healthy to do this longer,

1252
00:51:53,944 --> 00:51:55,904
both mentally and physically.

1253
00:51:55,988 --> 00:51:58,240
You have to be healthy.

1254
00:51:58,490 --> 00:52:00,743
It's great if you could
take care of yourself,

1255
00:52:00,826 --> 00:52:02,036
but if you can't,

1256
00:52:02,119 --> 00:52:04,913
it's important to take care of each other.

1257
00:52:04,997 --> 00:52:07,583
- Yes.
- I want myself, Chan-hyuk, our family,

1258
00:52:07,666 --> 00:52:09,752
and the people in our company

1259
00:52:09,835 --> 00:52:12,046
to take care of each other

1260
00:52:12,129 --> 00:52:15,424
and go the distance. That's my goal.

1261
00:52:15,507 --> 00:52:16,508
I see.

1262
00:52:18,802 --> 00:52:19,970
So...

1263
00:52:20,721 --> 00:52:23,182
- now that you've heard our story,
- Yes.

1264
00:52:23,432 --> 00:52:26,602
how much would you pay
for <i>The Happy Prince?</i>

1265
00:52:26,685 --> 00:52:29,271
- You want to know the price
- Yes.

1266
00:52:29,897 --> 00:52:31,231
- of this book?
- Yes.

1267
00:52:33,692 --> 00:52:36,320
Now, I've listened to your life story.

1268
00:52:38,614 --> 00:52:39,698
Just now,

1269
00:52:41,075 --> 00:52:43,619
I've set a price for this book.

1270
00:52:44,203 --> 00:52:45,245
I'm excited.

1271
00:52:45,329 --> 00:52:47,206
AKMU's favorite book. The price is...

1272
00:52:49,917 --> 00:52:52,211
<i>Long Long Night</i> by Ruri!

1273
00:52:54,630 --> 00:52:55,631
<i>Long Long Night!</i>

1274
00:52:56,757 --> 00:52:58,759
<i>Long Long Night!</i>

1275
00:53:00,135 --> 00:53:01,053
<i>Long Long Night.</i>

1276
00:53:01,136 --> 00:53:02,971
Here you go.

1277
00:53:03,055 --> 00:53:05,140
ONES WHO LOST EVERYTHING
FIND REASON TO GO ON THROUGH EACH OTHER

1278
00:53:05,432 --> 00:53:09,937
This book follows
the last white rhinoceros in the world

1279
00:53:10,562 --> 00:53:12,981
and a young penguin born from a bad egg

1280
00:53:13,065 --> 00:53:15,109
who spend countless long nights together

1281
00:53:15,401 --> 00:53:17,236
in search of the ocean.

1282
00:53:17,319 --> 00:53:19,113
- It already sounds so nice.
- Yes.

1283
00:53:20,114 --> 00:53:23,492
We have a song called "Last Goodbye,"
also known as "Long Day, Long Night."

1284
00:53:23,575 --> 00:53:25,619
- Yes.
- The title reminds me of that.

1285
00:53:26,704 --> 00:53:29,081
Our paths may be rough sometimes

1286
00:53:29,581 --> 00:53:31,667
and they might ruin our feet.

1287
00:53:32,084 --> 00:53:35,504
But despite that, we walk the path

1288
00:53:35,587 --> 00:53:39,675
because stars shine even on murky puddles.

1289
00:53:39,967 --> 00:53:41,969
That's what I think.

1290
00:53:42,344 --> 00:53:45,848
I hope your long, long nights
won't be lonely.

1291
00:53:45,931 --> 00:53:48,767
I hope that you'll be there
for each other,

1292
00:53:48,934 --> 00:53:52,187
and that you'll eventually
reach your own ocean.

1293
00:53:53,021 --> 00:53:55,399
I, Hocrates, will be rooting for you.

1294
00:53:55,607 --> 00:53:56,900
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

1295
00:53:59,611 --> 00:54:00,612
How was it today?

1296
00:54:00,696 --> 00:54:03,449
We read the book of AKMU's life together.

1297
00:54:05,242 --> 00:54:08,579
It was fun to talk
about the past after a while.

1298
00:54:09,121 --> 00:54:12,708
I don't know
if it's because you're 2,000 years old,

1299
00:54:12,791 --> 00:54:14,918
but you're a great interviewer.

1300
00:54:15,002 --> 00:54:18,338
I have nothing but respect for Hocrates.

1301
00:54:19,506 --> 00:54:22,259
Respect is not what I aim for. It's love.

1302
00:54:22,342 --> 00:54:23,302
I love you.

1303
00:54:25,429 --> 00:54:27,347
You two make a great pair.

1304
00:54:28,182 --> 00:54:29,933
I was feeling great today.

1305
00:54:30,267 --> 00:54:32,936
I think I did a good job
leading the conversation.

1306
00:54:33,020 --> 00:54:34,646
- I think it went well.
- Yes.

1307
00:54:34,813 --> 00:54:36,690
The cutest neighborhood in the world.

1308
00:54:36,774 --> 00:54:37,691
Where is it?

1309
00:54:37,775 --> 00:54:38,817
- Kangho-dong.
- Kangho-dong.

1310
00:54:38,901 --> 00:54:41,028
Yes, <i>Hodong's Bookshop</i> in Kangho-dong.

1311
00:54:41,111 --> 00:54:44,281
Today, we heard about AKMU's tasty life.

1312
00:54:44,364 --> 00:54:46,325
That was a great read!

1313
00:54:46,408 --> 00:54:48,410
<i>Thank you for the great read today.</i>

1314
00:54:48,494 --> 00:54:50,329
<i>- Thank you.</i>
<i>- Goodbye!</i>

1315
00:54:51,747 --> 00:54:52,998
Wait a second.

1316
00:54:53,665 --> 00:54:55,918
I like reading different lives
at my bookshop,

1317
00:54:56,126 --> 00:54:58,170
but the operating costs are no joke.

1318
00:54:58,587 --> 00:55:00,255
I'm sure there's a book that will help.

1319
00:55:00,798 --> 00:55:02,216
Oh, the business bestseller!

1320
00:55:02,841 --> 00:55:03,842
That's right.

1321
00:55:04,927 --> 00:55:06,887
The bestselling business book.

1322
00:55:07,346 --> 00:55:09,223
This book comes to mind.

1323
00:55:09,431 --> 00:55:10,307
What?

1324
00:55:10,849 --> 00:55:13,185
Kim Sung-han, the head of Coupang Play?

1325
00:55:13,435 --> 00:55:15,479
<i>Product Owner,</i> or PO.

1326
00:55:15,562 --> 00:55:18,148
A product owner is
someone in charge of everything,

1327
00:55:18,482 --> 00:55:20,317
from launching a service
to customer satisfaction.

1328
00:55:20,651 --> 00:55:22,611
They are like a mini-CEO.

1329
00:55:23,028 --> 00:55:26,156
"What makes a service beloved by users?

1330
00:55:26,240 --> 00:55:29,910
A service should start
with an obsession with the users."

1331
00:55:29,993 --> 00:55:33,705
That's right!
You have to be curious and persistent.

1332
00:55:33,789 --> 00:55:35,457
IT WILL HELP IN RUNNING THE BOOKSHOP
Very persistent.

1333
00:55:35,541 --> 00:55:37,042
If he's the head of Coupang Play...

1334
00:55:37,125 --> 00:55:39,211
Where should I put this book?

1335
00:55:39,461 --> 00:55:40,712
I'll put it right here.

1336
00:55:41,505 --> 00:55:42,506
Then...

1337
00:55:43,215 --> 00:55:45,884
we'll have a season two...

1338
00:55:47,052 --> 00:55:48,971
LEE SE-DOL
I came to sell a book.

1339
00:55:49,054 --> 00:55:50,806
The only human who has won against AI.

1340
00:55:50,889 --> 00:55:52,599
I want to carry you like this.

1341
00:55:52,683 --> 00:55:54,017
- I carried many people like this.
- I see.

1342
00:55:54,101 --> 00:55:55,102
HOCRATES ADORES HIM
It brings me back.

1343
00:55:55,185 --> 00:55:56,395
I'm not so sure.

1344
00:55:56,478 --> 00:55:57,813
Not sure that you'd lose.

1345
00:55:57,896 --> 00:55:59,022
Am I going to win?

1346
00:55:59,106 --> 00:56:00,065
You're Se-dol.

1347
00:56:00,148 --> 00:56:01,233
Of course I'll win.

1348
00:56:03,527 --> 00:56:06,488
HOCRATES IS HAVING THE TIME OF HIS LIFE

1349
00:56:06,572 --> 00:56:08,699
WHO IS AKMU?

1350
00:56:08,782 --> 00:56:14,663
21ST CENTURY BARDS WHO ARE PURSUING
INSPIRATION UNLIKE ANYTHING BEFORE

1351
00:56:39,563 --> 00:56:41,565
Subtitle translation by Cayle Kim
